Civil rights group issues travel warning for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Coloured People has issued a warning for people of colour travelling to Missouri due to the state's discriminatory policies and racial attacks.
"The NAACP Travel Advisory for the State of Missouri, which is scheduled to take effect by August 28, 2017, urges African-American travellers, visitors, and Missourians to pay special attention and exercise extreme caution when travelling through the state, as a number of questionable race-based incidents have recently occurred throughout the state and are noted here," the group's statement reads.
A recently passed Missouri law making it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, as well as the state's law enforcement agencies disproportionately targeting minorities, prompted the group to issue the travel warning, the NAACP said.
"You have civil rights violations happening to people.
They're being stopped because of the colour of their skin, they're being beaten up or killed," Missouri NAACP President Rod Chapel told the Kansas City Star.
"We're hearing complaints with such frequency that we haven't heard before."
It is the first such warning the organisation has issued for a state in the US.
The group cited incidents such as racist offenses against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, 28, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders died under questionable circumstances earlier this year after he ran out of gas while travelling across the state and was taken into custody by Missouri police without being charged with a crime.
The council also points to a recent report from the Missouri Attorney General's office showing that black motorists in the state are stopped 75 per cent more often than whites.
"The recommendation is that people be aware and let their families, friends and co-workers know what could happen in Missouri," Chapel said.
"People need to be prepared, whether it's bringing bail money or letting relatives know they are travelling through the state."
Missouri recorded 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI's Hate Crimes Reporting Program, which ranks the state 16th in the country for the number of such violations.
The travel warning is also a response to a new Missouri law that would make it harder to sue a business for housing or employment discrimination.
Previously, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) had issued travel warnings for Texas and Arizona after the states passed immigration laws requiring local law enforcement to arrest people for immigration violations, which the ACLU believes will contribute to further racial profiling.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently advocacy groups have used the measure in response to certain laws and trends within the US.
Is nothing sacred anymore?
Now the Trump White House is taking on the Statue of Liberty
The surest sign of regime change is when they start attacking the statues.
Americans value them as much as any other - hence the carefully orchestrated overthrow of Saddam Hussein in Baghdad's Firdos Square in 2003.
Stephen Miller, one of the Trump regime's key ideologues, certainly knew what he was doing when he took a symbolic axe to the Statue of Liberty in a heated argument with CNN's Jim Acosta over the president's proposals to drastically restrict legal immigration.
To be fair, Miller wasn't attacking the statue itself.
A horde of boat owners and Liberty impersonators would have lynched him if he had.
But he did attack its significance, and in particular the significance attributed to it when the famous poem by Emma Lazarus was added to its base in 1903, 17 years after the monument was completed.
As Miller berated Acosta, "I don't want to go into a complete thing about history here, but the Statue of Liberty is ... a symbol of American freedom that lights up the world.
The poem you refer to that was added later and is not part of the original Statue of Liberty."
Miller is factually correct, but as he put it himself, it's not really about history.
It's about the contemporary response to the stirring words of Lazarus, the only ones in which a state invites not just any old immigrants, but the poorest of the poor: "Thy weary, thy poor, / Thy harassed masses yearning to breathe free, / The wretched refuse of thy rich shores."
There was never a time when the "wretched refuse" was more visible on our screens.
Miller did not engage in literary criticism - he made it clear that these people are not welcome in Trump's USA.
This conflict over the meaning of a statue is part of a broader political and cultural conflict: it is, in fact, a conflict over the meaning of America.
Lazarus - and her friends who campaigned to place her words at grassroots level after her death - knew very well that they were performing a highly political act.
The sculpture was intended to show the links between French and American republicanism by depicting the female embodiment of freedom in a worn-out classical pictorial representation.
Lazarus changed this meaning: in her poem, the female figure is no longer abstract - she has been given a voice.
And she gives herself a completely different name: Mother of Exiles.
The linking of the poem to the image is a brilliant feminist coup and a devastating attack on American nativism.
And just as Lazarus changed the meaning of the statue, the right wing people have long wanted to change this back.
The great screamer Rush Limbaugh, a sort of John the Baptist for the coming of Trump, argued in 2010 that the Statue of Liberty was not inviting anyone, but rather an early neoconservative bringing the American flame to the benighted world: "Lady Liberty leads the way.
She is supposed to carry the torch of freedom from the United States to the rest of the world.
The torch is not to light the way to the United States."
Quite unusually, Limbaugh is on to something here.
The meaning of the statue is entirely a matter of point of view perception.
The great imaginative act of Lazarus was to see it as it was seen by exhausted, miserable but hopeful people after long and often terrible voyages on the decks of ships.
It is literally about seeing the world from the perspective of people seeking refuge and a chance to improve their lives.
Her statue speaks to them the words of hope and welcome they need to hear.
And that, of course, is not the perspective Miller and Trump ever want to acknowledge.
Their torch is not to light the way, but to ignite the hatred that is their only source of power.
World Cup 2017: Neil Black praises Scottish members of Great Britain team
Eilidh Doyle recalls a time when only two Scots were part of the Great Britain team
UK athletics performance director Neil Black says the 16-strong Scottish contingent in the World Championships squad "will make a massive contribution to the team".
A record number of Scottish athletes have been selected for London 2017, which starts on Friday.
Black believes that "something special is developing in Scotland" and that UK athletics has something to learn from it.
"We welcome it and we're trying to understand it and we're going to keep it going until we figure it out," Black said.
"I speak to people in the Scottish Institute of Sport and they think it has something to do with what they have done.
Scottish athletes think it has something to do with what they have done.
British athletics: it's something to do with what they've done.
And also with the guy on the street corner.
Whatever the combination of circumstances, it's absolutely brilliant."
Several of the Scottish athletes are medal contenders, including Laura Muir and Andrew Butchart - who will be competing against Sir Mo Farah in the 5,000m, while Eilidh Doyle has been voted team captain by the squad.
"Eilidh is quite humble.
Her captaincy speech was incredible," Black said.
"A number of athletes, whether they were Scottish or wherever they live or train, walked out of the room feeling very proud and they were very motivated.
The passion and genuine feeling that Eilidh naturally brought was great."
The Commonwealth silver medallist, who will be competing in the 400m hurdles at her fifth World Championships, says it is "incredible" that there are 16 Scots in the British team.
Scotland's previous best total of athletes at the World Championships was seven, achieved in 1983 and 2015.
Middle-distance runner Muir leads the way, setting five British and two European records last year.
She will compete in the 1,500m and the 5,000m heats.
Chris O'Hare, who runs 1,500m, is another Scot to watch after a great season that included winning the British Team Trials and the Anniversary Games.
Doyle recalls her first World Championships when the only other Scot on the team was Lee McConnell.
The team captain says she is "immensely proud" of the fact that many of her compatriots are not only part of the team, but in some cases will be in the mix for medals and finals.
"The special thing about being team captain is that it was voted for by the other members of the team, so it was a great honour anyway, but knowing that my teammates voted for me and chose me makes it very special for me," she added.
"Obviously I'm very proud of all the Scots that are part of the team.
It just shows how far we've come.
And they're here as established athletes, athletes who want to get on podiums.
As for my captain's speech?
Yes, I think it went well.
I just pointed out that we are very fortunate in this situation because we have a home World Cup.
So it's really important to build on that home support and benefit from the fact that we're back in the Olympic Stadium.
I get a second chance to go out there and compete and it's just going to be such a great atmosphere out there."
Blocking critics via Facebook: Don't run for public office if you can't take the heat from constituents
The father of our country knew something about bad press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it wasn't long before newspapers slammed him for everything from domestic policy to his political principles.
He scolded when criticised, sure.
But he didn't silence his critics.
For in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech may be taken away - and, dumb and dumb, we shall be led like sheep to the slaughter."
That brings me to Maryland to Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to work on being more like Washington.
Hogan's staff has blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their opinions on his official Facebook page.
And the American Civil Liberties Union sued him over it earlier this week.
The governor's staff dismissed the lawsuit as frivolous, and the online commentary was full of a backlash of "So what?" .
"It's just Facebook," many people said.
But it's important.
And it's especially important when it's a guy like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in an overwhelmingly Democratic state who is amazingly popular.
He has the second highest approval rating of the nation's 50 governors.
Hogan is not a reactionary hothead.
He has shown a firm hand in running his state and strict adherence to principles.
He has also been adept at using Facebook as a primary means of connecting with his constituents and gamely debuting his hairless head after chemotherapy on his page.
Therefore, blocking people from coming to the governor's page - which is a public forum designated as official and staff paid with public tax dollars - is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions, arguing that blocking the comments was nothing more than moderation.
But it's too easy to use the image of trolls or spammers or hateful people cracking the whip online.
The Post spoke to some of the real people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, a business owner and a pastor, not trolls.
They all said their comments were respectful, thoughtful and not profane.
The priest quoted the Bible in his post and appealed to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Attorney Lakshmi Sarma Ramani of Bowie, Md. was not hateful, but she questioned hate crimes.
"I politely commented that I was disappointed that there was no response to hate crimes and other breaking news," she wrote in the comments section of The Post.
"I don't appreciate this idea either, when a number of people take a stand on the same issue they are more likely to be disregarded by some as a so called collective effort and not recognised as a large group of concerned citizens."
What the governor's staff called a "concentrated spam attack", others would probably call "advocacy".
The Facebook era makes it easy to tailor a message by simply blocking a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It's much cleaner than in the old days when the same thing would have been done, that staff would have been dispatched to collect and burn newspapers with critical editorials or arrest and silence protesters.
But that is exactly what is happening digitally.
Hogan is not the first public official to be criticised for bashing Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from his Twitter feed.
One of the first milestones on the issue fell last week in Virginia.
The chair of the Loudoun County Board of Supervisors violated the First Amendment, according to US District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria, when she banned a constituent from her Facebook page.
And in Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R) also received a visit from the ACLU over his use of Facebook and Twitter.
That shouldn't be so hard.
In Washington's day, the age of affordable postage had a similar effect to the internet.
Newspapers multiplied in number between 1776 and 1800, and anonymous letter-writers pounced on his leadership.
And even then, Washington had anonymous trolls.
People using pseudonyms like "Juricola," "Valerius," "Belisarius," and "Portius" all wrote letters to newspapers slamming Washington's decisions.
Petitions criticising his stand on the Treaty of Amity, trade and shipping with Britain overwhelmed his office, according to historical documents collected by the George Washington Project's Online Papers.
But he did not silence them.
Freedom of speech, dissent and discourse are part of the foundation of our nation.
And true leadership means accepting that.
Ronan Rafferty hopes for domestic comfort at the Renaissance Club
Former European No 1 Ronan Rafferty will be hoping for domestic comfort over the next three days as the Renaissance Club in East Lothian hosts the 25th edition of the Scottish Senior Open.
The Northern Irishman, who led all the way to the final round last year next door at Archerfield Links before losing to Paul Eales, has been linked with the new venue and is acting as tournament ambassador on behalf of club founder and CEO Jerry Sarvadi.
"I've seen the Renaissance Club built and we're seeing it achieve its glory with this event," Rafferty said.
"The players will see this course at its best, it's in great condition.
Jerry did a great job in setting this place.
He is a keen supporter of this game and is proud of his achievement here.
This is a great showcase for this course."
England's Eales is looking forward to defending a championship for the first time, although he has won on both the European Tour and the European Challenge Tour in his 32-year career.
"This feels really special," said the Southport-based player.
"I didn't get to defend the Extremadura Open because it was withdrawn the year after I won it.
To come back to this part of the world is magical.
It's a wonderful place to play golf.
The memories from last year are coming back and it was special for me and my wife Sharon to win here last year.
It was a really special time and one we will always cherish."
Gary Orr, who joined the European Senior Tour after turning 50 earlier this year, returns to action on home soil.
The event will be his first Scottish appearance since the Aberdeen Asset Management Scottish Open in 2013.
"It always means a bit more when you play at home," said Orr, the Helensburgh man.
"You want to do well but you also feel that extra pressure.
I really enjoyed playing again and I played some solid golf.
I'm happy with how it's gone so far."
Joining the trio in the field are former Masters winner Ian Woosnam and senior major champions Paul Broadhurst, Roger Chapman, Mark James and Mark McNulty.
Orr and former Ryder Cup captain Sam Torrance are among the six Scots in the field, the others being Andrew Oldcorn, Stephen McAllister, Bill Longmuir and Ross Drummond.
Admission is free, parking is £5 per car with one occupant and £10 per car with two or more occupants.
All proceeds will go to Prostate Cancer UK.
Poverty and death in Indonesia's gold country
When Bardina Degei cooks dinner, she doesn't use a cooker.
In fact, she rarely uses a pot.
In her wooden house in Enarotali, the capital of Paniai regency in Indonesia's troubled Papua province, the housewife usually puts a sweet potato - locally called a "nota" - directly into the fireplace.
After half an hour, the charred tuber is removed and devoured with eager, unwashed hands.
Degei sits on the dirt floor - she has no furniture - where she also carries out her daily chores, such as washing clothes with murky water from the nearby swamp.
A bucket in a roofless room serves as a latrine.
As the youngest of her husband's four wives, she was not assigned any fields.
Polygamy is common here.
Of course, working late can be dangerous: Most village men are unemployed, and many drink heavily, and there are the soldiers here.
"No one dares to walk around the village after 5pm," she says.
It's a rare glimpse into daily life in the highlands of Papua, a former Dutch colony that was absorbed into Indonesia in 1969 after a controversial referendum when only 1,026 elders were asked to vote by raising their hands in public in front of occupying forces.
An existing movement agitating for independence against Dutch rule quickly turned against the Jakarta government, which maintains control over the region and bars foreign journalists or rights observers from it.
In 2003, the province was officially divided into Papua and West Papua, with the independent Papua New Guinea part comprising the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is desolate. The trip involves a 90-minute flight from the provincial capital Jayapura to Nabire and then a 5-hour morning drive by rental car.
There is no public transport.
The town of about 19,000 people consists of wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences and corrugated iron roofs that have been transformed by rust into various shades of yellow-brown.
Very few Indonesians have made their journey here, let alone journalists and virtually no foreigners.
Before Christian missionaries arrived, Mee Pago Papuans worshipped a god called Uga Tamee.
There were other changes too.
"We were not used to wearing these clothes," says Degei, pointing to her vibrant hand-woven turban, dark shirt and light skirt.
"Before, we only had leaves on our bodies."
Papua is Indonesia's poorest province, where 28% of people live below the poverty line and have some of the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it is also Indonesia's gold country.
The world's largest and most profitable gold mine, Grasberg, owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is just 60 miles from Paniai, a highland province the size of New Jersey with a population of 153,000.
In 2015 alone, Freeport mined US$3.1 billion worth of gold and copper.
In addition, Papua has timber resources worth an estimated US$78 billion.
However, these riches are a source of misery for Papuans, who ensure that Indonesia's powerful military maintains a suffocating presence.
A 2005 investigation in the New York Times reported that Freeport paid local military personnel and units nearly US$20 million between 1998 and 2004, including as much as US$150,000 to a single officer.
Papuan demands for greater autonomy threaten this golden goose and are treated mercilessly.
According to activists, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed and thousands have been raped, tortured and imprisoned by the Indonesian military since 1969.
Mass killings in Papua's tribal highlands in the 1970s became genocide, according to the Asia Human Rights Commission.
In the region alone, Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters last year.
"We Will Lose Everything" reads a 2016 report by the Archdiocese of Brisbane, which included accounts of atrocities in the previous year, such as unlawful executions and torture - rape and electrocution being particularly popular, according to another report - and the brutal crackdown on peaceful demonstrations.
"It's difficult to count the number of victims because incidents happen every week," says Andreas Harsono, Indonesia researcher for Human Rights Watch.
The screws have intensified as Papua's resources bring an influx of settlers from other parts of Indonesia.
The province's population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but demographics are changing as Muslim economic migrants arrive from the populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi.
Javanese warung canteens sell fried chicken and gado-gado, a mixed vegetable served with peanut sauce.
Local people struggle to keep up here.
"The migrants have started selling chicken and vegetables at the traditional market cheaper than the local Papuans," explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai local who moved to the provincial capital Jayapura for work.
"It has cost the local Papuans - the mama-mama [women] of Papua - their market."
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, popularly known as Jokowi, promised to address inequalities and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter secured 27 of Papua's 29 districts - including Paniai - on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta.
But little has changed in Papua, and today locals feel betrayed.
"Our hearts are broken because we voted for Jokowi in 2014 with the expectation that he would fulfil our hopes that justice would be restored," says You.
Indeed, Paniai suffered a low point just two months after Jokowi's inauguration in October.
On 7 December 2014, a group of 11 children were outside singing Christmas carols in front of a campfire in Enarotali when two Indonesian soldiers on a motorbike burst through the darkness.
The startled children told them to turn on their headlights.
One of the soldiers took offence at their tone and later returned with four soldiers, according to local pastor Yavedt Tebai.
The soldiers, who had been drinking, chased and beat the group with their rifle butts, victims and witnesses said.
Then one of the soldiers fired into the group of children.
One child, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was beaten so badly that he fell into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government commission building was set on fire and things escalated the next day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered on a football field in front of the local police station and military command centre to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the Waita dance - running in circles and imitating a bird song - of Papua's Mee Pago tribe.
Some protesters began hurling stones at police and military posts.
As tempers flared, soldiers were sent an order over an internal radio: "If the crowds resist more than three times, shoot them dead," said an official document obtained by TIME, which was not released to the local media.
Yeremias Kayame, 56, the head of Enarotali's Kego Koto district, saw the looming danger and called for calm, urging the crowd to return home.
No one was in the mood to listen.
"When I turned around, I was suddenly shot in my left wrist," he told TIME on the veranda of his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired, but says the bullet came from the ranks of soldiers gathered here.
"It was crowded, many shots were fired," he adds.
Local man Alfius Youw was hit three times, according to his cousin who witnessed the shooting.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him," Yohanes, who like many Indonesians goes by only one name, told TIME in sombre tones.
"I saw he was dead ... I kissed him."
Papua Police Chief Inspector Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers were only "securing" their station because it was under attack.
"We have to defend ourselves when people threaten to kill us," Papua Police spokesperson Commissioner Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015.
"It is a matter of life and death."
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more injured.
News of the killings did not reach Jakarta until the following day 'filtered'.
Three weeks, Jokowi gave an impassioned speech in Jayapura in which he expressed sympathy for the families of the victims and vowed to address the historic abuses in Papua.
"I want this case to be solved immediately so that it will not happen again in the future," he said.
Security Minister Wiranto said in October 2016 that he was setting up an extrajudicial mechanism to settle historical human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
"Most of the violations occurred a long time ago.
Some were in the 90s and early 2000s.
The point is that we are committed to addressing these violations, but there are processes that need to be gone through," he said.
Then Wiranto backtracked when he spoke to TIME in Jakarta on 5 June, saying he had no plans to set up a grievance mechanism in Papua.
Instead, "everything will be regulated by law," he said.
Wiranto, whom the UN has charged with "crimes against humanity" that claimed more than 1,000 lives in East Timor's bloody 1999 independence vote, said 11 cases of human rights violations in Papua had already been settled, including the Paniai incident.
Families of the Paniai victims received such claims with grim disbelief.
"I have been interviewed four times in the last three years, but there has been no progress at all," Yohanes said.
"I am tired."
He says that years later, he still lives in fear.
"I am scared," he says.
"I am afraid of being arrested by the military, afraid of being shot."
His brother Yacobus echoed the sentiment that people in Paniai are afraid to discuss the incident.
He says he was beaten by the military after he helped bury four of the victims.
"After I buried the bodies, the military came looking for me," he says.
The shooting has not stopped.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police fired on villagers in Paniai's Deiyai neighbourhood.
One person died and 17 others were injured, including children, during a confrontation between villagers and the manager of a construction company who refused to take an unconscious man to hospital.
The man, 24-year-old Ravianus Douw, who drowned while fishing in a nearby river, died on the way to hospital.
Agitated villagers protested outside the company's site office.
Police said the villagers threw stones at officers, who responded by firing warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) began firing at the crowd, killing one.
"We were so panicked, we are afraid there will be revenge," said 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the injured being rushed here, TIME reported.
"I hid in my house for two days."
The Deiyai Parliament has called for the officers involved to be held accountable and for the police mobile brigade to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a trouble spot for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development is strengthening the discontent of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribesmen who live in the green highlands of Papua.
Many joined the "Free Papua Movement" (OPM), the rebel army that claims to defend Papuan rights by instigating sporadic attacks and kidnappings of Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders are from Paniai, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Yudas Kogoya.
In response, thousands of people have been arrested and arbitrarily detained in Paniai in recent years, under the pretext of "safeguarding national sovereignty".
Some never reappear.
Among the people of Papua, Paniai is known as "a tragic, forgotten place".
Poverty fuels discontent.
The little rice sold in Enarotali is too expensive for locals.
Bread is just as out of reach.
People here grow everything they eat: mainly nota and fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the job of the women, who can each work four or five fields of sweet potato.
They keep most of the harvest for the family, while the rest is sold at the local market.
Ten pieces of nota cost only 10,000 Indonesian rupiah (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities have grown between the indigenous Papuans and the new migrants who have arrived in greater numbers since new flight routes to Nabire airport opened.
The few jobs that do exist in the region tend to go to the better educated and wealthier migrants.
Papuans rarely have the capital or the necessary skills to run their own businesses competitively.
"The young people are not interested in staying in the village ... because there are no jobs or money here," says John Gobai, chairman of the Paniai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps the eyes of the world away from Papua.
Moreover, restrictions on reporting keep international media tense.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua for failing to coordinate with related institutions, despite being given rare permission to film.
According to Phelim Kine, deputy Asia director at Human Rights Watch, promises made during Jokowi's election campaign to lift restrictions on reporting to promote transparency and development have not been realised.
"There are new dangers for foreign journalists trying to report from Indonesia's troubled easternmost provinces of Papua and West Papua: Visa denial and blacklisting," he said in a statement.
Lack of press control means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua's immediate neighbours.
In March, six Pacific nations - Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands and the Solomon Islands - called on the UN Human Rights Council to investigate the "various and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Paniai shooting.
These same countries have historically supported the OPM.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir rejected the group's allegations, telling journalists in Jakarta: "Indonesia still has a democratic system and there is a free media, so it's difficult to cover up evidence of human rights cases."
Local people want more foreign governments to take note.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by human rights ambassador Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on 4 May, locals broke their silence and urged him "We want freedom," according to a source who also attended the meeting but wished to remain anonymous.
Indonesia has another presidential election in 2019, but Papuans say they are unlikely to vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a person who has good intentions, but he is surrounded by the people involved in the Paniai shooting," says Gobai, the chairman of the tribal council.
He wants Jokowi to know that apart from living under the constant threat of a predatory military, the Paniai people are in poor educational and health services.
Gobai says the Paniai people, like other Papuans, see their vote for Jokowi as a "debt" he must repay.
"They don't need money, they just want justice," he says.
Despite the threats and intimidation, families of Paniai shooting victims carried out one last symbolic act of defiance: the body of one victim was buried in a compound just across the road from the police and military station.
They know that justice may never come to them, but at least they will not let those responsible forget their crimes.
"A member of our family was killed," Yacobus says with his head down.
"What else can we do?"
Fire grips Dubai's 'Torch' skyscraper for second time
A fire found its way through one of the world's tallest residential towers in Dubai on Friday, forcing hundreds of residents to flee the 337-metre, 79-storey building.
It is the second fire to sweep through the skyscraper, coincidentally called the Torch Tower, in just two years.
The building was evacuated, no injuries were reported, and there was no immediate word on the cause of the blaze.
"We were asleep and we got up at the sound of the fire alarm and people shouting.
We ran down the stairs and it took about 10 minutes to get down from the 50th floor," one resident, who gave his name as George, told Reuters.
Dubai's civil defence authorities said firefighting units were extinguishing the blaze and cooling the building at around 4:00 a.m. local time (00:00 GMT).
The government said it was working to provide shelter for those affected.
The incident may revive questions about the safety of materials used in the exteriors of high-rise buildings around the world.
An investigation by the management of the Torch building after its fire in 2015 found that most of the damage came from cladding, the exterior covering used for decoration or insulation.
In the UK, police said they believed the system of panels for insulation and cladding at London's Grenfell Tower may have contributed to the rapid spread of a fire in June that killed about 80 people.
More than 1 in 5 US travellers bring prohibited items on plane, survey finds
A survey of airline passengers found that more than 20 per cent knowingly or unknowingly smuggled prohibited items past US Transportation Security Administration checkpoints, including at least 6 per cent who boarded the plane while inadvertently carrying prohibited knives or other bladed objects.
Less than 1 per cent claimed they belatedly discovered they had mistakenly travelled with firearms, ammunition or explosives.
The survey of more than 1,000 people - conducted by a jet charter service, Stratos Jet Charters Inc - also found that younger travellers were more likely to flout the rules.
Of the respondents who admitted to knowingly trying to fly with something prohibited by TSA, 19.7 per cent were Millennials, compared with less than 15 per cent who were Generation X members.
The most common items intentionally slipped past TSA agents were food and liquids.
More than 3 per cent admitted to knowingly carrying bladed items through security, while 2.2 per cent of female respondents and 3.7 per cent of male respondents also confirmed intentionally bringing prohibited drugs onto the plane.
The company said it surveyed travellers across the country to find out how many had accidentally brought contraband through airport security and how many had done so intentionally.
Unsurprisingly, the people most likely to carry contraband - knowingly or unknowingly - through security were those flying most frequently.
However, the company points out that TSA guidelines are somewhat complicated and confusing.
People are often unsure what liquids they are allowed to carry or how much of them.
So it's no surprise that the largest amount of items seized by the TSA are prohibited liquids.
For a while, people thought the TSA might consider books contraband.
Liquids are allowed on domestic flights, but not on international flights.
EPA chief Pruitt backs down over stalling of Obama-era rules to cut emissions
A day after being sued by 15 states, Environmental Protection Agency chief Scott Pruitt retracted his earlier decision to delay implementation of Obama-era rules to reduce emissions of smog-causing air pollutants.
Pruitt presented the change as his agency proving more responsive to the needs of state environmental agencies than previous administrations.
He did not mention the lawsuit filed against his previous job in a federal appeals court.
At issue is a deadline that expired on 1 October for states to meet 2015 standards for ground-level ozone.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay compliance for a year to give his agency more time to study the plan and avoid "interfering with local decisions or impeding economic growth."
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma's attorney general before being appointed by President Donald Trump, has long been a staunch opponent of stricter environmental regulations.
Since arriving in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved to block or delay regulations opposed by the chemical and fossil fuel industries.
Wednesday's sudden reversal is the latest legal setback to Pruitt's regulatory rollback agenda.
Last month, a federal appeals court in Washington ruled that the EPA administrator exceeded his authority when he tried to delay implementation of an Obama administration rule requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks.
In a statement released Wednesday night, Pruitt suggested that his about-face on ozone standards simply reinforced the EPA's willingness to work with states through the complex process of meeting the new standards in a timely manner.
"Under previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet implementation deadlines and then waited to be sued by activist groups and others and set the implementation date in a settlement," said Pruitt, who sued the EPA more than a dozen times in his previous job.
"We don't believe in regulation by litigation, and we take deadlines seriously.
We also take the law seriously and the authority it gives us."
Still, the EPA's statement said Pruitt will at some point use his "authority to delay and all other legally available authority" to ensure regulations are "based on sound policy and the best available information."
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a more comprehensive rewrite of the ozone rules.
A bill approved last month would delay implementation of the 2015 rules by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet been brought to a vote in the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states that sued the EPA this week, said the group intends to keep up the legislative pressure.
"The EPA's reversal - after our lawsuits - is an important win for the health and safety of those 6.7 million New Yorkers and the more than 115 million Americans directly affected by the smog pouring into their communities," Schneiderman said.
New York was joined in this case by California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont and Washington and the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone is formed when pollutants from cars, power plants, oil refineries, chemical plants and other sources in the atmosphere react to sunlight.
The resulting smog can cause serious respiratory problems in sensitive groups of people, and contribute to thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health officials and environmentalists cheered Pruitt's surprise change of course.
"It's disturbing how much pressure it takes to get this sensible move from the person responsible for protecting the air we breathe," said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
"We must continue to fight the Trump administration's ideological crusade to pander to polluters and their special interests."
