Moore's Ford massacre: activists reenact racist lynching as call for justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury drove through a group of spectators in rural Monroe, Georgia, and rumbled towards Moore's Ford Bridge.
Before the car, which had four black passengers and a white driver, could reach the bridge, a group of white men with guns stepped forward to block its path.
The leader of the mob - a middle-aged man in a pinstriped suit - took a long drag on his cigar and peered scrutinisingly through the windscreen.
Inside, the occupants hovered in fear.
"We want that n ---- r Roger!" the man roared.
"Get him out of the car!"
Screams shattered the silence as a young black man was dragged from the passenger seat.
Fortunately, this horrific scene played out on 22 July is only a reenactment.
But when a noose is then thrown around the neck of "Roger", almost everyone in the audience heaved very real sighs.
Since 2005, civil rights activists have returned to Moore's Ford Bridge to re-enact the night two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey - were lynched by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946.
No one was ever charged with the murders.
"It's really inconceivable that in all these years, not one person has been arrested - even though we see them in our communities, even though we know who they are," said Tyrone Brooks, who helps organise the reenactment.
"It's a smudge on a story, but it's a burden on our souls."
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia state congressman and lifelong civil rights activist.
For him, the reenactment serves as a dramatic call to action and represents an annual reminder to the Monroe community that a wrong has never been righted.
"We want prosecution, we want termination, we want healing, we want reconciliation, but first we must get justice," he said.
"We cannot get to healing and reconciliation until we get justice."
A medical examiner places a sheet over the body of one of the victims of the Moore-Ford lynching on July 27, 1946.
According to FBI files obtained by NBC News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties were suspects in the lynching trial.
But none was ever charged.
Although the suspects have remained at large for decades, civil rights activists say the dual motivation for the lynchings has always been known throughout the city: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court decision allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote in the summer primary for the first time.
Around the same time as the election, according to the FBI, black sharecropper Roger Malcom stabbed a white landowner, Barnett Hester, during a fight - allegedly over a woman.
Brooks said the rumour in town was that Hester had slept with Malcom's wife, Dorothy, and that the baby she was carrying was not her husband's.
On 25 July 1946, Loy Harrison, a prominent white landowner, paid $600 to get Malcom out of jail, the FBI said.
He was accompanied to the jail by Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey.
But as they then pulled away from the jail and approached Moore's Ford Bridge, a lynch mob surrounded the car.
"As it turns out, it was Harrison who prepared and ordered the murders," an FBI report concludes here.
"It is also apparent that there was a conspiracy between state and local law enforcement that not only participated in the murders, eliminated evidence and covered up the identities of witnesses."
Brooks puts it even more succinctly.
"It was a voting rights massacre," he said.
"They were all killed to send a message to black people in this community that if you register and if you vote, this is what will happen to you."
For nearly a decade, Cassandra Greene has directed the annual reenactment of the Moore Ford Bridge Lynch murders.
Her portrayal is vivid, poignant and is grounded in a kind of deep racism that many would like to believe no longer exists in America.
It's hard to watch, and even harder to look away, but Greene said that's the point.
"We don't want to talk about lynching because then we're confronted with its ugliness in all of us," she said.
"But I can't relate to you if you don't want to listen to me or hear what I've been through".
Rehearsals for this year's production began in June, and on the first day, nearly 30 actors - a dozen white and the rest black - crowded into a room and listened as Greene launched into a well-rehearsed overview of the play.
Wade Marbaugh is Greene's co-director here.
He has played the role of the head clan member for years, but said the role never gets any easier.
"I feel dirty because I'm not like that," Marbaugh said.
"But I think it's very important to keep that history alive because we don't want to go back to those days."
Across the room, actors Darrius Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, who play Roger Malcom and Barnett Hester, rehearsed their lines.
The play opens with Malcom shouting at Hester and badgering him, angry that he has slept with his wife Dorothy.
"I said, n --- er, get off my property!"
Rascona returns fire.
There is a pause.
And then everyone (at least all the black actors) bursts out laughing.
Greene laughs the loudest.
"What?!" asked Rascona.
He is alarmed and confused.
Was I being too harsh?
"No," said Greene, still chuckling.
"I just don't think white people said 'n --- er' back then."
"Yes they did," quipped one of the other black performers.
"You just gotta hit the hard 'r.'"
And right there, the energy in the room shifts, a sense of camaraderie replacing discomfort.
Everyone is preoccupied with getting this right, not just because of the game, but because of the memory of the four people killed.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Rascona says the N-word, he says it sharply and emphatically.
Absolutely no one laughs.
This repetition ends violently and quickly.
There are screams, gunshots and then silence.
A woman, dressed in a mourning gown, stands over the bodies of the actors and performs Billie Holiday's mournful eulogy "Strange Fruit".
Her voice breaks with every other word.
About a hundred yards behind, a group of about four dozen spectators wipe sweat and tears from their eyes.
The audience is almost evenly divided between black and white.
A couple have travelled from Ithaca, New York, to see the performance; many come just down the street.
They have all experienced nearly eight hours of Georgia's oppressive humidity as Brooks leads them on a pilgrimage to the gravesites of the Malcoms and Dorseys.
Up to this point, the murders have remained anecdotal, but now, standing on the same land where the Lynch murders took place, the air feels haunting.
As the final notes of the song fade out, Greene invites the crowd to come closer and inspect the bodies.
Children crouch by their heads, registering the fake blood and still bodies, whispering to each other.
"They're not really dead," one little boy murmurs, as if to remind himself.
After a few minutes, Greene thanks the crowd - and suddenly it's over.
The actors throw away the lynch rope and wipe their tears.
Bradshaw hugs Marbaugh, the man in the suit who played the clansman.
Nick Rascona hugs two of his fellow actors and then breaks down crying in their arms, the emotional weight of the performance finally breaking through to him.
"It's okay," one of the women whispers.
"We know this is not in your heart.
You did this for a reason."
Later, the audience sits down to dinner with the actors.
At one table, a white couple from Atlanta chat animatedly about the reenactment with a black couple they just met.
Denise Duplinski struggled to find words for the feeling the performance left her with.
"It's hard to hear these horrible words and actions ... Coming from people who look like yourself and they're doing this because they look like you," she said.
"What this is really doing to me makes me think that the lynching is still going on," she added, "today it's just called police shootings."
In the same room, Tyrone Brooks holds court at his table, eating and reminding people about civil rights.
He said he has already started planning next year's performance.
"The re-enactment is inspiring in a way because it describes the horror of what we endured, but it's also a learning moment," he said.
"The thing is, if we don't learn from it, it can happen again.
Those who don't study their own history, those who don't know their own history, are doomed to repeat it."
