New results of Swedish asylum age assessment tests released
The latest results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, who were subjected to a new method of medically assessing their age, show that more than 80 per cent of those tested are older than 18. But not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Authority (Rättsmedicinalverket) started conducting the tests last year.
They are intended to make the assessment of age more accurate during the asylum process, after the Swedish Migration Board (Migrationsverket) was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were minors.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent out 6,880 cases to be tested and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty per cent (2002) were judged to be 18 or older, while in a further 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency judged that the person was "possibly 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "may be under 18".
The tests are only carried out in cases where the person's age is in question.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent over the past few months.
"We don't see a big difference in the statistics over the past months, the numbers are pretty constant," he told The Local.
The high proportion of cases where the person was judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean the asylum seeker lied about their age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said there were 442 cases "suggesting that the person examined was 18 or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, it found that in 243 of those cases the person had openly said they would turn 18 this year.
The method of medical age assessment, which involves taking x-rays of wisdom teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, which are then analysed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticised in some quarters.
One sceptic is Karolinska Institute endocrinologist Claude Marcus, whose work involves assessing people's biological maturity to see if they went through puberty earlier or later than usual.
"I had reason to think about it, and I don't think that's the way the measurement should be used.
To judge biological age in this way is very uncertain.
If we can't tell for sure, we shouldn't pretend we can," he told the Metro newspaper.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of incorrectly assessing a child as an adult is low.
The biggest risk is when the person is just under 18, in which case it's about 10 percent."
