How football's financial rules affect Neymar's move to Paris
Rules aimed at preventing unfettered spending by European football clubs will not disrupt Neymar's world-record transfer from Barcelona in Spain to Paris Saint Germain in France.
Some consequences are yet to come for Paris Saint-Germain from UEFA, as the governing body that oversees the European game has the power to ban teams from entering the prestigious Champions League tournament.
Financial fair-play rules, set up by UEFA in 2011, mean PSG will eventually have to prove that Neymar's transfer was financed without incurring huge losses.
Barcelona paid 222 million euros ($262 million) to buy the Brazilian out of his contract and Neymar will receive a salary that will be tens of millions of dollars a year.
Here are some of the financial aspects of Neymar's move to France.
PSG can certainly loosen the purse strings to sign Neymar and bring him to a galaxy of other stars, given the team's funding from the energy-rich ruling family of Qatar.
Clubs are allowed to spend big money to acquire players, but must counter it with legitimate revenue streams that allow them to break even point in their football-related business.
FFP was conceived by Michel Platini after his election as UEFA president in 2007.
The former French player believed that clubs who had taken on huge debts in their quest for success were effectively cheating and risked bankrupting themselves if banks or owners withdrew their support.
In 2011, FFP shifted from focusing on clubs' debts to monitoring their losses.
The change meant that the business model Roman Abramovich originally used at Chelsea in 2003 - buying a club with potential and then investing heavily to improve the team and build a global brand - would become a tougher proposition.
During the current three-year FFP assessment period, which runs until 2018, clubs can take losses of €30 million.
And although Platini fell from grace from the presidency in 2015, his UEFA successor Aleksander Ceferin remains committed to discouraging excessive spending.
"Certainly FFP is not dead and we will certainly strengthen the rules for the future," Andrea Traverso, who is in charge of FFP at UEFA, told The Associated Press last week.
Although PSG paid Neymar's buy-out clause in a lump sum, they can spread the amount for accounting purposes over the duration of his contract.
Neymar signed a five-year contract, meaning that the buy-out amount of €44.4 million for the next five years can be recognised in the financial statements.
The first wave of FFP sanctions in 2014 hit PSG with the heaviest sanctions along with Abu Dhabi, owned by Manchester City.
PSG was fined €60 million ($82 million at the time), which was later reduced to €20 million - and ordered that team membership for the 2014/15 Champions League season remain limited to 21 players instead of the normal 25.
UEFA is on the lookout for clubs that might try to outsmart its financial watchdog by inflating their revenues through companies linked to a club's owners.
While a Qatari company could sponsor PSG, if the value of the sponsorship exceeded standard market rates, UEFA would not allow this to be considered legitimate income.
This is exactly what happened in 2014 when UEFA ruled that the value of PSA's sponsorship was inflated by the Qatar Tourism Authority.
It was reported that part of PSG's payments to Neymar could come via payments from the Qatar 2022 World Cup organising committee.
But PSG and Qatar 2022 have denied that Neymar will become a World Cup ambassador and such a manoeuvre could be easy for UEFA regulators to figure out.
The sanctions against PSG so far mean UEFA will be even more alert to any attempt to circumvent the rules.
UEFA had no preliminary talks with PSG about Neymar's transfer, people familiar with the situation said on Thursday.
They spoke to The Associated Press on condition of anonymity because they were not authorised to discuss the PSG situation.
The latest published reports show PSG made a profit of more than €10 million in 2015/16 on a turnover of €542.4 million.
The accounts for the last financial year have yet to be published.
PSG expect Neymar's arrival to be a boon for sponsorship deals, merchandising and shirt sales.
The club expects sales to increase by at least 30 per cent after the signing.
The Spanish league was clearly irritated to see one of football's best players leave, and it tried to prevent Neymar's departure by claiming PSG were in breach of the FFP.
"It is a clear case of" financial doping" with the club and the state," La Liga president Javier Tebas told Spanish daily AS in reference to Qatar's ultimate ownership of PSG.
Arsenal manager Arsene Wenger, whose club is owned by an American sports tycoon, shares La Liga's reservations about a state financing a club.
"It is the consequence of ownership and that has completely changed the whole landscape of football in the last 15 years," Wenger said on Thursday.
"Once a country owns a club, everything is possible.
It becomes very difficult to respect financial fair play because you can have different ways or different interests when a country has such a big player to represent a country."
Nostalgia goes niche in 'Wet Hot American Summer' and 'Comrade Detective'
This iteration of history is at once nostalgic for the characters' glory days of the '80s, for the '90s grunge era (when masterminds David Wain and Michael Showalter made the sketch comedy "The State" for MTV), and for itself - that is, for 2001, before its stars, like Elizabeth Banks, Amy Poehler and Paul Rudd, went on to bigger things.
As a cultural artefact, it's equally a parody and an embodiment of our Facebook-enabled era of permanent memories.
But as a franchise, it feels like it's running out of time.
"First Day of Camp" worked surprisingly well, and not just because of its absurdist humour (it included an original story for a talking can of vegetables voiced by H. Jon Benjamin).
By sticking to the core of the gag - middle-aged actors playing horny kids growing up - they still managed the impossibility of reclaiming the last part of the joke.
"Ten Years Later", with its adults now playing adults, is less emotionally rooted and its parody goes more by the watering-can principle, including a riff on '90s stalker movies like "The Hand That Rocks the Cradle" ("The Hand That Rocks the Cradle").
At one point, a character rummages through an Apple powerbook, some inline skates and "a bunch of other stuff from 1991".
Many of the central stories are the same.
The amiable Coop (Mr Showalter), now a novelist, still hasn't forgotten Katie (Marguerite Moreau).
Victor (Ken Marino) still hasn't lost his virginity.
And there's another crazy-bad plot involving Ronald Reagan (also Mr Showalter), now backed by George H. W. Bush (a well-done impression by Michael Ian Black).
As always, the digressions are the best part of the franchise.
It's especially fun to see the eternally young Mr Rudd showing off Matt Dillon's lower lip beard from Singles, whose former big-man-on-camp Andy now feels like an old geezer.
It's the moments of random insanity that could fuel this franchise like some kind of repetitive "Seven Up!" series until it reaches what I assume is its logical conclusion, "Wet Hot American Summer: Twenty Years Later," the final scene of which will show the gang attending the movie premiere of "Wet Hot American Summer."
"Comrade Detective" on Amazon, meanwhile, evokes a different kind of nostalgia: the Cold War revival of "The Americans," the film "Atomic Blonde" and even "GLOW" with its East-versus-West wrestling iconography.
Created by Brian Gatewood and Alessandro Tanaka, the Rhys Thomas-directed comedy purports to be a found TV series: a Romanian drama of the 1980s with the two policemen as friends, two officers from Bucharest fighting for truth, atheism and the path of Marxism-Leninism.
The leads - a hard-boiled Gregor and an idealistic Iosef - are played by Florin Piersic Jr. and Corneliu Ulici, whose dialogue is dubbed into English by Channing Tatum (also an executive producer) and Joseph Gordon-Levitt.
It's a brilliant idea.
But it's not much more than an idea.
There are some nice gags to watch (the police spend time watching chess on TV, as Americans might do with football).
And the roster of famous voice actors - including Jenny Slate, Nick Offerman, Mahershala Ali and Chloë Sevigny - makes for a decent game of 'figure out the voice'.
But "Comrade Detective" is so committed to the verisimilitude of a desperate propaganda drama - an assassin wearing a Reagan mask is included - that it often plays as one.
At six long episodes, it drags, and the comedy isn't fast or frequent enough.
"Comrade Detective", edited to a shorter length, could better deliver its agitprop satire as Gregor and Iosef repeatedly visit the American Embassy, whose lobby is always occupied by two fat men devouring a pile of hamburgers.
The message for the imagined communist audience is that Western culture can make anything into fodder for a binge.
The fictional Romanian creators were not wrong: we even do it with our own recent history and theirs.
The Bank of England will keep interest rates at 0.25%
The Bank of England is expected to announce later that interest rates will remain unchanged after weak economic growth and weakening inflation dampened speculation of a rise.
The Bank of England has warned that economic growth will remain "sluggish" as it kept interest rates on family incomes amid intensifying pressures.
Policymakers on the Bank's Monetary Committee (MPC) voted 6-2 to keep rates at 0.25%, with fewer members seeking a rise this month as weak economic growth weakened support for an increase.
In its quarterly inflation report, the Bank cut its growth forecasts for 2017 to 1.7% and for 2018 to 1.6% and warned that pressures on household incomes would continue, with inflation still expected to rise to just under 3% in the autumn.
But she signalled that interest rate rises would be needed in the next few years to rein in inflation fuelled by Brexit and said borrowing costs may have to rise more than expected in financial markets.
Members also voted to withdraw part of the mammoth stimulus package issued a year ago after Brexit.
It will call for time on the funding plan to provide cheaper finance for banks from next February, although it was said it is now expected to provide £15 billion more under the scheme - with £115 billion.
Minutes after the rate decision, the bank said: "In the MPC's central forecast, gross domestic product (GDP) remains weak in the short term as pressures on real household incomes continue to weigh on consumption."
On interest rates, it reiterated that "some tightening of monetary policy" would be needed to cool inflation and a "somewhat larger" degree than markets expect.
Markets currently forecast the first hike in the third quarter of next year and another in 2020.
However, the Bank stressed that increases would be "gradual" and "limited".
The Bank's downwardly revised growth forecasts for this year and next year compare with the 1.9% and 1.7% it forecast in May.
It maintained its growth forecast at 1.8% in 2018.
The pound fell against the dollar and the euro after the news.
The pound fell 0.5% to $1.31 and fell 0.4% to €1.11.
The decision to make no change comes after recent disappointing growth figures dampened rising expectations of a rate hike, with GDP rising to 0.3% in the second quarter from 0.2% in the previous three months.
Growth is expected to be 0.3% in the third quarter, although the Bank expects it to recover slightly towards the end of the year.
The latest inflation report offered little enthusiasm for households hit by rising inflation and marginal pay rises, saying the tightening will get worse before it gets better.
It added that monetary policy cannot "prevent" the income slump over the next few years, but added that wages will recover "significantly" by the end of its three-year forecast.
The economy will also be boosted by rising demand for UK goods, due to the weak pound, which will offset some of the lower consumer spending.
The decision comes a year after the Bank cut interest rates to 0.25% last August following the shock EU vote that caused the pound to fall.
The Bank estimates that it is likely to take four years for this to fully hit prices and the economy.
Before the Bank's latest verdict on interest rates, calls for a rate hike had been rising as inflation increased pressure on hard-pressed households, with three policymakers calling for a rise to 0.5% in July.
Inflation fell to 2.6% last month from 2.9% in June, although the Bank said this was expected and it would pick up in coming months.
The Bank said the overshoot relative to its 2% target was "entirely" due to the weak pound.
Andrew Montlake, director at Coreco Mortgage Brokers, said: 'Given the recent fall in swap rates, the mortgage market is likely to become more competitive again as lenders look loudly for deals and look to end the year in a positive manner.
The market is looking particularly good for those with existing deals coming to an end and those taking out new mortgages, and many with fee-free options and low rates are becoming more popular."
NHS (The National Health Service) to prescribe controversial HIV drug to 10,000 people
Patients will be able to access "transformative" HIV prevention treatment from September following a High Court battle against NHS funding for the drug.
NHS England announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) taken before sex, which can reduce the risk of infection by around 86 per cent in high-risk patients, will now be delivered by the health service to an estimated 10,000 people via an initial three-year trial.
It agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal last year upheld a High Court ruling that the NHS had the power to pay for PrEP despite claims that local authorities should fund it.
The move announced on Thursday was hailed as an "important new intervention" by NHS England chief executive Simon Stevens, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) called it a "defining moment".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be among the first to allow people to sign up, with more clinics to follow in October before it is rolled out across England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a course of HIV medication taken before sex to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Studies have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission in those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means that there is just enough medication in a person's body to prevent HIV infection.
Such medication can be taken every day or so as early as two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include gay or bisexual men, transsexuals and people with HIV-positive partners who have not been successfully treated.
Clinics will identify eligible participants who consent to the study, including men, women, transgender people and individuals who have a partner whose HIV status is not known to be controlled by antiretroviral treatment.
People who live in England and are registered with a GP can also sign up for possible participation at their local participating sex clinic.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England signed a contract to supply the drugs this week following an international competitive procurement.
The trial aims to assess the full potential of PrEP by gathering clinical evidence on how it is targeted, taken up and implemented on a large scale.
Stevens said, "This major new intervention should complement and overtake the wide-ranging and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
It is another milestone in more than three decades of progress in addressing one of humanity's greatest health challenges."
Deborah Gold, Chief Executive at NAT (National Aids Trust), said, "This is a defining moment in the fight against HIV.
PrEP, when targeted at people in need and at risk, offers the opportunity to transform the English HIV epidemic.
From September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to this NHS-funded trial in England to develop a new tool that is truly individually controlled and not subject to negotiation with a partner, leading to the improvement of many, many lives.
We warmly welcome this announcement."
Ian Green, Chief Executive of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said, "The priority now must be to ensure that the trial is rolled out quickly across the country and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
Now that PrEP testing medicine has been procured, we are well on our way to protecting more than 10,000 people infected with HIV."
Sharon Hodgson, Shadow Health Minister, said, "The start of the PrEP process is welcome and overdue after months of delays and reluctant implementation by the government.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to HIV prevention and ending the transmission of this life-changing infection.
This trial brings us one step closer to understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it is important that this trial is conducted across the country as soon as possible to protect people who are HIV-infected, and that it will help bring us one step closer to ending the spread of HIV in society.'
Living the big life: Mezzanine and clever designer tricks have transformed this small Earls Court flat into a lavish home
Joanne Leigh, a former banker with a passion for property, downsized from a large house in Knightsbridge to an Earls Court flat in 2014.
It's on the first floor of an elegant Queen Anne terrace - and it's a testament to the new design that Joanne hasn't packed her bags and sold.
"Before that I lived with my ex in Knightsbridge in a much bigger space," says Joanne.
"I was looking for something comparable to my price.
I was shown this flat in Earls Court and it had the same high ceilings.
I fell in love with it and made an offer that day."
Since the first viewing, the 1,000 square foot flat has been completely overhauled.
Originally a one-bedroom property with a convoluted layout - you had to walk through the kitchen to get to the bedroom - Joanne wanted to add storage and a mezzanine to make the most of the generous ceiling height.
"I wanted high ceilings, big windows, lots of light.
That was my requirement," she says.
To this end, she commissioned Notting Hill-based architecture and design studio Duck & Shed by Erfan Azadi to make the most of the 12.5ft ceilings and create a home that was not only a development but also a place for Joanne to live.
The ceiling wasn't big enough to fit two rooms on top of each other, so the architectural challenge was to create a mezzanine floor where people could stand.
Erfan had to think creatively to solve the brief.
"The steel plant is quite complicated," he explains.
"We had to arrange the spaces so that they were stacked on top of each other without having to bend down.
It wasn't just a matter of building a simple platform, but laying out the steel so that it was the right height for the function above or below."
This arrangement allowed Erfan to place two full-height rooms on top of each other - with plenty of added drama.
For the mezzanine, a classic copper light window by Retrouvius looks down over the glamorous living area.
Mirrored gold furniture, silver accents and vintage Serge Mouille lighting set the style for the scheme.
The use of mirrors plays a role in adding theatre, space and light.
A short corridor is mirrored at both ends to make it feel longer.
In the kitchen, the mirroring feels like a window into another room.
At the entrance, mirrored units provide space for all of Joanne's cutlery and glasses.
By creating the perception of a more glamorous space, the beauty of the living room can close off the kitchen when it's not in use.
Collapsible kitchens are nothing new.
What makes this one special is that it is a garage door.
"A bit of engineering went into it," explains Erfan of the steel-reinforced, veneered MDF door.
"It's counterweighted, so when you slide the door up, it slides very easily."
Clever use of space and storage enabled Joanne to gain an extra 16 sq ft, an extra bedroom and an improved layout.
"At the end of the day, you will sell the floor space - or how your property is valued," says Erfan.
"In a rudimentary form, a real estate agent will come in and do a calculation based on the floor size."
Here, they've managed to increase the floor area while using high-quality materials that give the space its luxurious edge.
"The materials are the things that touch you and therefore help create an emotional attachment in a home," says Erfan.
"You don't fall in love with the electrical sockets in the walls.
These are important, but they don't play with your heart."
It goes to show that a home can transform from something standard to something quite amazing through good design and increased square footage.
In fact, like Joanne, you might choose not to leave it.
Brothers fight over US$500 million property empire
Two brothers are in a dispute over one of Victoria's largest property empires, worth more than $500 million, four decades after their Italian family founded the dynasty.
Former 'Carlton Football Club' director and developer Colin De Lutis lives in a Toorak mansion just three doors down from his younger brother Paul. The latter has taken him to the Supreme Court to have it clarified how their property and business assets should be divided.
Paul had wanted to retire from the family business since 2014, but a sharp dispute over the split is taking place in the Supreme Court.
Together with their mother Anna, the brothers own 38 properties worth more than half a billion dollars, accumulated since the family bought a shop in Smith Street, Collingwood, in 1973.
There the family founded Westco Jeans and grew it into a chain of 160 retail shops.
It was sold in 1999 for $85 million.
That money was invested in real estate and De Lutis' portfolio now includes offices in the city centre, the Brunswick and Sorrento development areas, the Gold Coast and Mt Buller flats and suburban shopping centres.
Under an agreement with their late father, Colin - described by Paul as "the main operator and the dominant personality" in the De Lutis family - owns about two-thirds of the company's assets and Paul about one-third.
A court filing says this means Colin owns $316 million worth of property and Paul $176 million.
The division of property and cash has proved to be a problematic issue for Paul.
"The divisions proposed by Colin have left him with what I believed to be the best properties," he wrote in an initial affidavit in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failed mediations, the first Supreme Court hearing took place.
The brothers are now also fighting for control of the existing business - from which Colin claims Paul has excluded him.
Colin argues this is not true, but accuses Paul of incompetently managing some properties.
In an early affidavit filed by Colin, he says he hopes to settle the dispute.
"My Italian heritage dictates that family is the most important priority," he wrote.
Costs are mounting in the case, with hundreds of pages of affidavits, emails and reports from firms including Deloitte, Pitcher Partners and Charter Keck Cramer, and with leading lawyers including Allan Myers, QC, and law firms held by both sides.
Mrs De Lutis and her late husband Luigi were Italian immigrants who ran milk bars and delicatessens from the late 1950s and bought a business in Brunswick in the early 1970s.
They used the security to buy the Collingwood property where Colin opened the family's first jeans shop.
Colin says he started Westco there when he was "in my last years of high school, when Paul was a little kid (about 10 years old)."
Anna De Lutis says that she and Luigi, who died in 2012, hoped to pass their property on amicably to their sons.
"Luigi often said to me that he never wanted the brothers to end up in court," she wrote.
Two other brothers, Mark and Luke, are no longer part of the De Lutis group of companies, with Colin claiming that Mark was paid $10 million and Luke $26 million when he left.
Both Luke and Mark, Paul says, "have become bitter about the terms of their financial separation".
Colin has kept a very low profile, despite being a former AFL board member and, according to a 2015 biography by Eddie McGuire, the TV star's best friend.
Fairfax Media contacted Colin and Paul De Lutis and their lawyers.
Only Colin responded by text message to say "I really can't say much" because the case was before the courts.
"It is very, very sad that my brother Paul has decided to sue me and drag our family name through the courts," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a letter to the court that he had tried to meet his brother's demands.
"Our father would not have wanted Paul and I to end up in our current dispute," he said, adding that he was "still hoping for a resolution".
On Friday, that hope appeared to be over.
"Our matter will be resolved by the courts in the near future," Colin wrote.
Trump's new chief of staff plans to limit the president's media abstinence.
Others have tried and failed.
Maybe John F. Kelly can actually do it.
If so, he will be the first.
Politico reports that the new White House chief of staff plans to restrict the flow of information to President Trump - including news media reports - in hopes of keeping the boss on a more even keel.
Here's a piece by reporter Josh Dawsey:
"When John F. Kelly, the new White House chief of staff, met with senior staffers on his first day on the job, he outlined a major problem in President Donald Trump's White House that he wants to fix: bad information getting into the president's hands.
Kelly told staffers that information should flow about him - whether on paper or in briefings - because the president would make better decisions if he received good information."
Kelly's diagnosis makes sense, but others have tried to tame Trump by monitoring his media diet.
President Trump's relationship with television goes back decades - and now that he's in the White House, his TV ads are still going strong.
"When candidate Trump was upset about unfair coverage, it was productive to show him getting fair coverage from outlets that were persuadable," former campaign adviser Sam Nunberg told Politico in February.
Politico's Tara Palmeri wrote at the time that "the key to keeping Trump's Twitter habit under control, according to six former campaign officials, is to make sure his personal media consumption includes steady praise."
Okay.
But the idea that Trump's Twitter habit was ever "under control" is ridiculous.
Maybe these campaign officials know something the rest of us don't - that Trump's tweets would have contained even more dynamite without their interventions.
We'll probably never know about the tweets Trump didn't send.
If his staff have managed to keep trouble away from him a few times, their efforts have paid off.
But no one has been able to consistently prevent Trump from stirring up controversy.
Part of the problem is that in a White House made up of competing parties, people keep trying to advance their own agenda by presenting Trump with material that potentially furthers their views of the world.
Politico - all over this story - reported in May on the advisers' penchant for feeding the president dubious information for strategic reasons.
This was one example described by reporter Shane Goldmacher:
"Current and former Trump officials say Trump can react like a volcano to negative press clippings, especially those with damaging leaks, and that he is bent on finding out where they came from.
That's exactly what happened in late February when someone maliciously gave the president a printed copy of an article from GotNews.com, the website of internet provocateur Charles C. Johnson, which accused deputy chief of staff Katie Walsh of being "the source behind a bunch of leaks" at the White House.
Although Johnson has been permanently banned from Twitter for harassment or that he has offered no concrete evidence or that he has made false accusations in the past and recanted them.
Trump read the article and started questioning staffers about Walsh."
Goldmacher added that then-chief of staff Reince Priebus and White House general secretary Rob Porter "tried to implement a system to manage and document the paperwork that Trump receives."
How did that work out?
Kelly is trying to do the same three months later.
Perhaps he will prove a more effective manager than Priebus, but Trump is still his impulsive self, and his advisers still strive for influence.
These immutable factors make Kelly's mission very difficult.
Travellers negotiate a ditch and return to 'millionaire row'
Some of the West Midlands' wealthiest homeowners are again at loggerheads with some determined travellers who have negotiated a council-drawn ditch to reclaim a field in front of their mansions.
The travellers have parked their 20 caravans in a field outside an affluent Solihull street called Millionaire's Row.
They have brought horses, babies and an army of vans with them, having only been turned out in May but not deterred by a ditch dug by the council to prevent their incursions.
The tactful group found a gap in the defences and pushed their vehicles through a section that remained unobstructed to find a way through.
Angry residents pressed Solihull Council, who said it was "useless to deal with the problem".
