Italy toughens tone on NGO migrant rescue boats
Italy has warned NGOs that operate migrant rescue boats in the Mediterranean that they will not be allowed to continue doing so unless they abide by new rules governing their operations.
"If NGOs do not sign a new code of conduct, it is difficult to see how they can continue to operate," Interior Minister Marco Minniti said in an interview with Turin daily La Stampa.
Minniti's warning came a day after Italian authorities seized a boat belonging to the German aid organisation 'Jugend Rettet' because its crew had effectively collaborated with human traffickers in a way that facilitated illegal immigration.
The aid organisation, which has only been in operation for a year, declined to comment on detailed allegations made by Italian prosecutor Ambrogio Cartosio.
"For us, saving human life is and remains our top priority. So we are very sorry that we cannot operate in the search and rescue zone at the moment," the organisation said in a statement on social media.
"We can only assess any allegations that are currently being made after we have gathered all the information and can assess the situation."
Italian authorities had been monitoring the 'Jugend Rettet' boat, the Iuventa, since October.
Its crew are believed to be taking on board inflatable boat migrants delivered directly to them by human traffickers, allowing the smugglers to depart so that the boats can be used again.
At least one such encounter allegedly took place just 1.3 miles off the Libyan coast, according to the prosecutor's file, the contents of which were published by Italian media.
The crew is suspected of defying the authority of the Italian coastguard, which oversees rescue operations in the zone for humanitarian reasons and not for any other motive.
Under the Code of Conduct, boats like the Iuventa are required to have, above all, an Italian police officer on board to monitor their activities.
Only three of the nine NGOs involved in search and rescue operations have so far agreed to abide by the code: Save the Children, MOAS from Malta and Pro-Activa Open Arms from Spain.
The latter said on Thursday that the new rules were considered unnecessary but acceptable as they would not bring "significant changes or impediments" to its rescue operations.
Among those refusing to sign is Nobel Prize-winning organisation Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF).
Minniti, meanwhile, said the number of migrants arriving in Italy after the rescues had dropped sharply in recent weeks, suggesting that efforts to strengthen the Libyan coastguard and work with local mayors had borne fruit.
"In the last few days we have started to see light at the end of the tunnel," the minister said.
He announced plans for further talks this month with Libyan mayors on economic development initiatives, and with Chad, Niger and Mali on measures to reduce the number of migrants leaving those countries in the hope of reaching Europe.
Michelle Carter convicted over texts urging Conrad Roy to commit suicide
A Massachusetts woman has been sentenced to two and a half years for encouraging her boyfriend to commit suicide through texts and phone calls.
Michelle Carter, now 20, will spend 15 months of her sentence behind bars and five years were suspended.
Carter was convicted in June of the involuntary manslaughter of Conrad Roy, who took his own life on July 13, 2014.
Roy's father said at Thursday's hearing, "My family is heartbroken.
My son was my best friend."
Carter was allowed to remain free pending the appeal.
She had faced a maximum sentence of 20 years, but her legal representatives argued that both she and Mr Roy suffered from mental illness.
Dressed in red trousers and a cream blouse, Carter stood there with tears in her eyes, her hands folded and her eyes downcast as she was sentenced.
"Her actions killed Conrad Roy," the prosecutor told the court.
"She ended his life to make her own better.
She took no responsibility," she said.
"She has shown no remorse".
But Carter's lawyer said it was a "terrible circumstance that she totally regrets".
Judge Lawrence Moniz, however, said he did not find that her "age or maturity or even mental illness had a significant impact on her actions".
A prosecutor read a statement from Roy's mother Lynn Roy that said "there is not a day that I do not mourn the loss of my beloved son.
I want him to be proud of me and how I am handling everything. I try to be there for his sisters despite all my pain that we will carry with us for eternity," it said.
Roy's sister, Camdyn Roy, testified that she was "haunted" by the realisation that she would never attend her brother's wedding or be an aunt to his children.
"To no longer have this one person that I have been with every day since I was born is a pain that I will always keep with me for the rest of my life," she said.
The case appears to set a legal precedent, as there is no Massachusetts law that makes it a crime to ask another to commit suicide.
Carter was 17 years old when Roy was found dead from carbon monoxide poisoning in a vehicle in 2014.
The case attracted national attention after Carter's text messages revealed she had encouraged him to end his life.
"Hang yourself, jump off a building, stab yourself, I don't know, there's a lot of ways," she said in several messages sent in the two weeks before his death while he was on holiday with his family.
In the moments before his suicide, she wrote: "You have to do it Conrad" and "All you have to do is turn on the generator and you will be free and happy."
Judge Moniz said Carter was seeking attention through Roy's death and ordered her to benefit from the case through some press.
The case has divided legal opinion.
Among the few to defend Carter was Amanda Knox, who was convicted of murdering her British roommate in Italy in 2007 before being acquitted two years ago.
Ms Knox, 30, published a commentary in the Los Angeles Times saying: "Michelle Carter deserves compassion and help, not jail."
Audi to change 850,000 diesel vehicles - carmakers face backlash
A day before Audi's announcement, BMW said it would offer to update the software in more than 350,000 vehicles.
BMW's chairman said the company believed "there are smarter options than driving restrictions", referring to European cities - including Munich, where BMW is based - banning or restricting diesel vehicles.
Daimler announced on Tuesday that it would modify three million Mercedes vehicles in Europe to reduce its diesel emissions.
None of the companies described the undertakings as a recall.
European carmakers have heavily promoted the use of diesel vehicles in Europe and the United States to help meet rules on carbon dioxide emissions.
But the nitrogen oxides that diesel engines emit are considered carcinogens and can cause asthma.
The cost for carmakers to install equipment to neutralise the fumes emitted by diesel vehicles is also increasing, making it difficult to keep the price of cars competitive.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel is also accused of coddling the powerful car companies and ignoring signs of the problem.
The companies are trying to avoid the mistakes made by Volkswagen, which used so-called defeat devices that could regulate emissions to comply with regulations when a car was being tested, but backed off under normal driving conditions.
Several Volkswagen employees have been indicted in the United States and others are under investigation on both sides of the Atlantic.
Last month, the former head of thermodynamics in engine development at Audi in Germany was arrested.
The former manager, Zaccheo Giovanni Pamio, is Italian and therefore not protected from extradition and could face trial in the United States.
Earlier this year, Audi became involved in German criminal investigations into Volkswagen after authorities accused Audi of installing a scheme to evade emissions regulations in Europe, and an enquiry focused on the United States was expanded.
The inclusion of Audi in the investigation could weigh heavily on Volkswagen: the luxury carmaker contributes disproportionately to Volkswagen's profits.
Lavender from Provence threatened by climate change
It has become a symbol of Provence in southern France, but there is a warning that it is under threat from climate change.
Lavender is declining because of conditions reminiscent of drought and because of disease-carrying insects, causing a major headache for scientists and farmers trying to find solutions.
Eric Chaisse, an expert at the CRIEPPAM agricultural research institute in Provence, said: "Lavender in Provence is effectively endangered because in recent years the plant has been exposed to the effects of climate change, which has brought much less rain in spring and much more in autumn.
This has an impact on the longevity of lavender.
There's also a small cicada, a microbacterium that transmits leafhoppers, and in very dry weather there are a lot of them."
And the stakes are high.
Lavender oil is not only attracting holidaymakers, it is also in high demand for perfumes and cosmetics.
Eric Chaisse said, "Instead of having very long plant ears with a large number of flowers, we have smaller ones that are underdeveloped and either missing or weakened.
So we have fewer essential oil parts."
Solutions being considered include better water distribution and slowing evaporation from the soil, but also spraying plants with a protective mixture of clay and water and developing varieties that are more resistant to drought.
The murder of a journalist underlines the growing threat in Mexico
The staff of the weekly newspaper Riodoce usually meet on Wednesdays to review their plans for covering the recent chaos in the state of Sinaloa caused by organised crime, corrupt officials and incessant drug wars.
But on this day, in the shadow of their own tragedy, they came together to talk about security.
They were told that it was important to change their routines.
Two senior journalists discuss what feels safer: taking their children to the office, who were the target of a grenade attack in 2009, or leaving them at home.
Security experts have written three words on a board at the front of the room: Adversaries, Neutrals, Allies.
They ask reporters to suggest names for each column - no proof is needed, perceptions and gut feelings will do.
There are drug smugglers, politicians, businessmen, journalists suspected of being on the payroll of the government or the cartels, a catalogue of criminals that make the chaos of Mexico dangerous.
There is no respite from the violence, and as bodies pile up across the country, more and more journalists are among them: at least 25 since President Enrique Pena Nieto took office in December 2012. 589 are under federal protection after attacks and threats, and so far this year there have been at least seven deaths in seven states.
Among the latter is their editor and their inspirer of Riodoce, co-founder Javier Valdez Cardenas.
"The biggest mistake is living in Mexico and being a journalist," Valdez wrote in one of his many books on drug-related violence.
His absence is deeply felt, although his presence is everywhere - a large photo of Valdez, showing his middle finger with the word "Justice", hangs on the façade of the Riodoce building. Two reporters in their thirties, Aaron Ibarra and Miriam Ramirez, wear T-shirts showing his smiling face with glasses or his trademark Panama hat.
The workshop takes place less than two months after his death, and the reporters discuss their shared issues, the trauma, their nightmares, insomnia, paranoia.
Although a special federal prosecutor's office was set up in 2010 to handle journalists' cases, it has opened only two criminal cases, according to the Committee to Protect Journalists.
As with most of the thousands of murders linked to drug trafficking and organised crime each year, the killers of journalists are rarely brought to justice.
In the case of Riodoce, they still insist on covering the Sinaloa violence, even though they are heartbroken and even though the terrain is now even more treacherous.
Without information about the killers, without justice, the meeting to discuss security has little use, Ibarra says.
"It is very foolish to waste my time in this workshop," he says.
"Until we know the why, we distrust everyone."
On the morning of 15 May, Valdez left the office of the Riodoce newspaper in the state capital of Culiacan.
He only managed to drive a few blocks before his red Toyota Corolla was stopped by two men. He was forced out of his car and shot 12 times, presumably because of the name of the newspaper - which translates as "Twelfth River".
The gunman drove off in his car and damaged it nearby.
Valdez was 50 years old.
He left behind a wife and two adult children.
Rumours tend to fly freely in Culiacan.
But on the subject of Valdez, there is virtually nothing but silence.
Since Guzman's arrest last year and extradition to the United States in January, Sinaloa had become one of the country's bloodiest battlegrounds as rival factions fight here to fill the vacuum.
Never mind that someone or several people are shot dead in the street every day in Sinaloa, or that the cemetery is full of ornate, two-storey mausoleums for drug kings that are bigger than many homes for the living.
Forget for a minute that there is a state of "tranquillity" when only one cartel is in control of the coastal state with its valuable ports and drug trafficking routes to the United States.
Despite this, and despite the fact that Valdez was aware of the dangers of his work, Ismail Bojorquez (60), a co-founder and director of Riodoce, is broken with guilt over not being able to protect his friend.
He believes two misunderstandings contributed to the murder.
First, there was the February publication of an interview with Damaso Lopez, a leader of one of the rival cartel factions in the war with Guzman's sons.
This publication may have angered the sons; suspected gang members bought up every copy of the issue as soon as it was delivered to newsstands.
The second mistake was not forcing Valdez to leave the country for his own safety after the seizure of another newspaper that had published the same story.
Valdez was a legend in Mexico and abroad, and his killing is considered a landmark in Mexican violence against journalists.
He had survived so long that his friends and colleagues assumed he would always be around.
He was a veteran reporter for Noroeste in 2003 when he joined five colleagues to form Riodoce and sold US$50 worth of holdings.
In Sinaloa, "it was impossible to do journalism without running into the narcotics problem," Bojorquez said.
Over time, the paper earned a reputation for bold and honest reporting, and sales and advertising increased.
Reporters loved being able to publish hard-hitting investigations without fear of censorship, and readers were intrigued by a publication where they could read stories that no one else dared to cover.
Eight years after founding Riodoce, she received the prestigious "Maria Moors Cabot Prize" for her reporting in Latin America.
That same year, Valdez won the 'International Press Freedom Award' from the Committee to Protect Journalists for his courage in pursuing the Mexican drug story wherever it led.
He freely admitted that he was afraid.
"I want to keep living," he said at the time of the CPJ award.
Drug trafficking in Sinaloa "is a way of life," he said in an interview with Rompeviento-TV last October.
"You have to do the job that falls to you as a journalist - either that or play dumb.
I don't want to be asked: what did you do in the face of so many dead ... why didn't you say what was going on?"
The Riodoce team misses Valdez, the joker who could swear like a dockworker, the friend who was generous with hugs and advice, a teacher who knew how to survive.
They trusted his routine.
He would always wear his hat.
He would always go to El Guayabo, the bar across from the office, and always sit at the same table there.
Now they ask: Was his love of routine his undoing?
His death has also forced them to question their own assumptions about how best to do their jobs while staying alive.
"They don't like you to deal with their wives, their children, their clean shops, their secret runways" to move drugs.
"These things were not allowed," Bojorquez said.
The result, even at the best of times, is a high degree of self-censorship and self-preservation.
Trusting your own instincts.
If it smells wrong, stay away from it.
The trouble is, said Riodoce editor Andres Villarreal, that "smell is a sense that can be fooled ... and then the thing happened with Javier."
The old rules, he and others say, no longer apply in Sinaloa - any more than they do in Tamaulipas, Veracruz, Guerrero and other states that are home to a toxic mix of lucrative smuggling routes, weak institutions and corrupt government officials.
The landscape is constantly changing.
In the room where Riodoce staff met for security training, suddenly no mobile phones were allowed. Days earlier, it was revealed that spyware sold exclusively to governments was being used to monitor journalists and activists in Mexico.
Outside, two police officers sought shelter from the 104 degree (40 ° C) heat in the shade of a tree.
They were assigned by the state government to protect Riodoce's offices in a four-storey building in a middle-class neighbourhood of Culiacan.
Half-jokingly, some of the reporters wondered if these officers were among the 50 percent of police officers the governor himself described as untrustworthy.
It has been months since the reporters went to the mountainous area where the drug gangs are under de facto control.
For this week's edition, Riodoce looked at three main stories.
There was the murder of the brother of former well-known boxer Julio Cesar Chavez in Sinaloa.
They also had an exposé on state spending that focused on the governor's hometown.
And there was a group that carried out a kidnapping in one of the most expensive restaurants in Culiacan, a block from the prosecutor's office.
There was no official word on who was kidnapped or how it happened, so caution was in order when it came time to write what everyone in town knows: that the restaurant is a favourite haunt of drug traffickers and authorities.
A reporter learned from public records that the restaurant was registered under the name of a politician belonging to the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), which has dominated all levels of politics for most of the century.
Recently, several PRI governors have been accused of high-profile cases of corruption.
Villarreal asked the reporter to write about previous incidents in the locale, including one in which a son of "El Chapo" Guzman escaped a military ambush.
Just a few months earlier, readers would have considered Valdez's column the best-informed source on the kidnapping.
"Before, we would have known what was happening," said Villarreal, 46, nicknamed "El Flaco" for his slender physique.
"Now all channels of communication with our sources are broken."
Valdez's office has been repurposed as a storage room for signs and stickers protesting the murders of journalists, as staffers have become something they never expected themselves to be: Activists on behalf of the press.
Reporter Miriam Ramirez grabbed a few signs and went to the prosecutor's office the next morning for a demonstration about another journalist.
Salvador Adame disappeared three days after Valdez was killed, in the western state of Michoacan.
A burnt body was discovered and officials say, based on DNA tests, that it is his.
Across the country, journalists have become more vocal, writing "SOS Press" on pavements and buildings in organised protests.
On this day, director Bojorquez is away in Washington trying to rally international support for justice in the Valdez case.
In a meeting with the governor of Sinaloa the day after Valdez's murder, Ramirez accused the authorities of spying on journalists and having them killed for telling the truth.
She has since asked to be reassigned by the government because she is concerned that her anger has hurt her objectivity.
Valdez had repeatedly said that journalists in Mexico were "surrounded" by organised crime, government officials involved in it and an indifferent society.
In his latest book, Narco-Journalism, he wrote that reporters are not only killed by drug gangs, but also on the orders of politicians and security forces who are in cahoots with organised crime.
The media watchdog group Articulo 19 attributed more than half of the attacks on journalists to police and civil servants last year.
"In Mexico you die because they want you to shut up," Ramirez said.
Obviously, the killings have a chilling effect.
No one forgets the death of blogger Maria Elizabeth Macias in the northern border state of Tamaulipas six years ago.
Her body was found along with a note allegedly signed by the Zetas cartel: "Here I am for my reports."
A computer keyboard and headphones lay next to her severed head.
Some outlets have chosen to close, like El Norte newspaper in the northern border state of Chihuahua after the murder of correspondent Miroslava Breach in March.
Others continue, as did El Manana of Nuevo Laredo after the murder of its director in 2004.
In 2010, Diario de Ciudad Juarez publicly addressed the drug cartels with a front-page editorial headlined "What do you want from us?"
Some journalists have fled their home states or even the country.
It is a painful decision.
It is hard to find work in exile, and they still watch the streets, looking for danger.
And sometimes they are hunted down, as apparently happened to photographer Ruben Espinosa, who was murdered in 2015 along with four women in a flat in Mexico City three months after fleeing Veracruz.
For those who stay behind and continue the work, it is a daily dance of risky choices.
Ibarra, who once wanted to be a poet, admits that the drug trade scares him.
"Mexico is going to hell, and that's why I became a reporter," he said.
At midnight last Friday, with the last edition already finished, Riodoce's editors were sitting on the pavement outside the office drinking beer when suddenly everyone's phones started buzzing.
A series of shootouts with gang rivals and security forces near the resort town of Mazatlan had left 19 confirmed dead.
The war continued to escalate, as promised by a series of cartel messages in the region.
From the curb, they posted the news on Riodoce's website via mobile phone.
The front page had to be changed the next day.
Sirens wailed nearby - another shooting in the area.
Bojorquez glanced at the policemen standing guard to see if they were on standby.
If they were scared at all, they didn't show it.
Beneath the enormous portrait of the newspaper's fallen founder, his middle finger visible to all of Sinaloa, Riodoce's staff followed his footsteps.
"How can you even think of closing," Bojorquez said, "when on the same day that Javier was murdered, the intern asked me to send her out to cover the street."
Dinosaur used camouflage to avoid its enemies
At first glance, it looks like a statue, albeit a terrifying one.
Now researchers have found that the first evidence of a Canadian miner's incredible rhino was so well preserved that experts have described it as the "Mona Lisa of dinosaurs".
It was so well preserved they could even tell that its scaly skin was a reddish brown - and they said it had something of a "troubled past".
The report in the journal Current Biology called it "the best-preserved armoured dinosaur ever found, and one of the best dinosaur specimens in the world".
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived in the mid-Cretaceous period between 110 million and 112 million years ago.
Its incredibly well-preserved condition has stunned researchers, who describe it as "truly remarkable"
According to reports in National Geographic, the armoured herbivore is the best-preserved fossil of its kind.
It was found by Shawn Funk while he was digging at the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on 21 March 2011.
He came across something that seemed out of place from the surrounding rock and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil he discovered was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
They spent the next six years uncovering the wild animal within the 2,500 pound (1,100 kg) lump of earth.
After all that hard work, the finished result is now ready to be unveiled.
"If you blink your eyes just a little bit, you could almost believe it was asleep," said lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display.
"It will go down in scientific history as one of the most beautiful and well-preserved dinosaur specimens - the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs."
Researchers have found that although this herbivore is covered in armour and resembles a walking tank, it was probably threatened by carnivorous dinosaurs.
The heavily armoured dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators and used a shielding technique known as counter-shadowing, which is also used by many modern animals.
This would have allowed it to blend in better with its surroundings and avoid its enemies, experts say, suggesting it was threatened by larger dinosaurs.
The 110-million-year-old creature from the nodosaur family first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Palaeontology.
Researchers have now studied the wild animal and named it Borealopelta markmitchelli after museum technician Mark Mitchell, one of a team who spent more than 7,000 hours carefully uncovering it.
The amazing preservation of the specimen allowed Dr Mitchell and an international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of scales and armour over its body.
They discovered counter-shading, a common method of defence in the animal kingdom, meaning that the top of the creature was darker than its underside.
Although counter-shading is common, the results are surprising because the size of Borealopelta far exceeds that of animals living today.
It suggests that the dinosaur was hunted by enough pressure from carnivorous dinosaurs that evolution favoured concealment of confrontation as a means of survival.
But most contemporary animals that use countershading - think deer, zebras or armadillos - are much smaller and more vulnerable as prey, signalling that this nodosaur faced a real struggle for survival.
"Strong predatory behaviour on a massive, heavily armoured dinosaur show how dangerous Cretaceous dinosaur predators must have been," Brown said.
Chemical analysis of organic compounds in its scales also shows that the dinosaur's skin was reddish brown.
Scientists continue to study the animal for clues about its life, including its preserved gut contents, to find out what it ate as its last meal.
They believe that when the dinosaur died, it got caught in a river and floated out to sea, where it sank on its back to the ocean floor.
At that time, Alberta was as warm as South Florida is today, and rivers and oceans probably spread much further inland than they do today.
"This nodosaur is truly remarkable because it is completely covered in preserved scaly skin, but it is also preserved in three dimensions and retains the original shape of the animal," Brown said.
"The result is that the animal looks almost exactly the same today as it did in the early Cretaceous.
You don't need to use much imagination to reconstruct it. If you squint your eyes just a little bit, you could almost believe it was sleeping."
The Cretaceous period was a time when giant theropods, carnivorous dinosaurs that stood on two legs, roamed the earth.
Although the king of them all, the Tyrannosaurus Rex, lived millions of years after Borealopelta, the armoured dinosaur was hunted by some of its more fearsome ancestors.
These include Acrocanthosaurus, a 38-foot-long (11.5m), six-ton monster.
The scientists, whose latest findings appear in the journal Current Biology, believe Borealopelta sank into the sea after death and was mummified in the mud.
The creature was found by Shawn Funk while he was digging at the Suncor Millenium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada, on 21 March 2011.
According to the museum, it is the best-preserved armoured dinosaur in the world, including skin and armour, and is complete from snout to hip.
The creatures averaged about 18 feet (5 metres) long and weighed up to 3,000 pounds (1,300 kg).
It contained two 20-inch-long spikes that protruded from its shoulders.
Researchers believe the armoured herbivore was swept across western Canada until a flooded river swept it into the open sea.
But the dinosaur's underwater burial preserved its armour in exquisite detail.
The fossilised remains of this particular specimen are so well preserved that the skin remains still cover bumpy armour plates along the dinosaur's body
As Michael Greshko has written for National Geographic, such a level of preservation is as 'rare as winning the lottery.
The more I look at it, the more confusing it becomes.
Fossilised remnants of skin still cover the bumpy armour plates that support the animal's skull.
Its right front foot lies at its side, its five fingers splayed upwards.
I can count the scales on its sole'.
How an activist came to learn the answer to the question, "Whose Streets?"
On 9 August 2014, Brittany Ferrell was shaken to her core.
Just one day after arriving in New York City, the St. Louis native was sitting on the bed of an Airbnb flat she was renting, scrolling through Facebook on her phone.
She stumbled across a post from someone in high school.
"Police just killed an 18-year-old kid and he's still on the street," it read.
Confused, as no one else on her feed had posted the information, she closed Facebook and opened Twitter.
A user with the handle @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted on her timeline.
The St. Louis-area rapper was live-tweeting the death of Michael Brown, an unarmed black 18-year-old killed by a white police officer in Ferguson, Mo.
He posted a picture of Brown's lifeless body sprawled on the street, where it would remain for four hours.
"This is wild," Ferrell thought to herself.
But death was nothing new to her and her community.
She put her phone down to return to tweets about people on Canfield Drive later that evening.
There were photos of the police tape and people screaming, and of a man claiming to be Brown's father carrying a sign that read, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
She watched a live feed of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, she said, another police officer unlocked his rifle and shouted, "I'm going to kill you.... Kill all the animals."
"That's not common," Ferrell recalled her saying.
"This is not the kind of killing we have become accustomed to and can call typical."
At that moment I felt chills.
I was angry and crying."
She booked a return flight and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., she picked up her 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided the two of them would drive to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary, "Whose Streets?", in cinemas from the 11th.
It's a story of survival and protest, love and loss, strength and resilience, as seen through the eyes of the people who live in the community and have filled the streets to demand answers.
As Ferrell drove to Ferguson with her daughter, who wore a floral dress and matching crown, the two discussed a conversation they had countless times before that morning "about the black experience and the black condition."
"You remember how I taught you when black people have to fight for what they believe in?" she recalled saying.
"We're going to Ferguson now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it wasn't right.
I couldn't take her," Ferrell said later.
"What happened today is a culmination of ... what happened in the past.
She needs to know it and see it and be brought up in it.
She needs to be well developed, not just activism and organising, but knowing the different layers of the black experience and the black condition and what we need to do to become free, to free ourselves.
Even if I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn't personally experience blatant racism, she's no different than the next black woman-child.
I feel like I would be doing her a disservice to keep her away from that."
The first stop when they arrived in Ferguson was on South Florissant Road, a location across from the police department that became a camp area as the activists waited for Officer Darren Wilson's possible non-indictment.
There, Ferrell and her daughter connected with a local business owner who was making lunch.
They prepared bags and helped pass them out to demonstrators.
Slowly, a new kind of activism began to take shape for Ferrell.
"My activism totally changed after August 9," she said, noting that as a student at the University of Missouri-St. Louis, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and health disparities in black communities.
"I had no experience in organising.
It all came."
Weeks later, Ferrell met Sabaah Folayan, one of the film's co-directors, during an evening demonstration.
Folayan said she and her cinematographer Lucas Alvarado-Farrar just wanted to "document" what was happening.
A question occurred to Ferrell: "Are you trying to document or are you trying to find a story to exploit?"
This scepticism was fuelled by countless cases of people, often white - in a community that benefited from their pain and resilience.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We had heard that people born and raised in Ferguson didn't have their voices centred, and we wanted to do it differently."
Folayan had already worked with then co-director Damon Davis, an area artist known for his activism around death row inmates.
His involvement brought Ferrell closer to the project, along with six other locals, the team of "Whose Streets?" followed in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This documentary is not someone talking for us or talking to us. We're talking," Davis said.
"That was the main thing for me, how these people are portrayed, because that's how I'm going to be portrayed."
The goal was not to focus on Ferrell's experience - to show that the movement is "not about a messiah leader, but a community coming together," Folayan said - she proved to be the most outspoken participant in the film.
As a result, documents from "Whose Streets?" show surprisingly personal aspects of Ferrell's life, as she falls in love and marries her wife.
"I felt like I was naked," Ferrell said, laughing when she first saw the finished product.
"But I understood that there has to be a certain vulnerability in this work and in humanising black people."
Moreover, Ferrell's story reiterates the role of black gay women in the broader Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the movement's three founders, who coined the film "BlacklivesMatter" on social media after the 2012 killing of black teenager Trayvon Martin, identify as gay.
"Black, gay women in leadership positions have carried the movement as a whole," Ferrell said, "and so we are constantly fighting on different fronts.
Black, gay women have to bear the brunt of everything."
Folayan agreed, noting that "the movement is really being sustained by black women and many black women."
However, she insists that "this is not an affirmative type of action" where Ferrell was chosen to be the heart of the film because of her identity.
"She was the person who stirred up that energy," she said.
"It's not a coincidence though she was front and centre because there's so much at stake in living at these intersections as a black, gay woman.
You can feel her energy through the screen."
By now, the news cameras in Ferguson are long gone, but the racial ties between the community and the police remain.
Ferrell is on probation for 2½ years for blocking a highway at a demonstration.
She describes the socio-political atmosphere of the area she calls home: "A mess."
Still, she clings to a chant, and she has felt committed to this memory since she took to the streets in Ferguson three years ago.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It is our duty to win.
We have to love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose - except our chains."
A fitting likeness: artist creates portraits with Chelsea Manning's DNA
In the centre of the room at Fridman Gallery in New York, there are many faces - white, black and brown, almost imperceptibly alike - hanging from the ceiling by cables.
The 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg from cheek swabs and hair clippings sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Manning sent the clippings from Fort Leavenworth prison, where the former intelligence analyst was serving a 35-year sentence after she made classified diplomatic messages public via the website WikiLeaks.
The new exhibition, which opened on 2 August, is called A Becoming Resemblance.
It is the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, whose discipline combined her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a trans woman and pioneering dissident whose conviction was commuted by Barack Obama when he had only three days left in office.
Dewey-Hagborg's algorithmic analysis of the DNA extracted from Manning, from which 30 portraits were created of what someone might look like with that genomic data, created a sharp, if somewhat intellectual, commentary not only on the malleability of DNA data - the many ways it can be interpreted and the inherent determinism of those interpretations - but also on identity.
Manning, who was born Bradley Edward but has been open about identifying as a woman since she was a teenager, was convicted in 2013 of 20 charges, including six violations of the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
Through prison, her image was suppressed, so much so that there was only one photo - a grainy, black-and-white selfie in which Manning is visibly uncomfortable sitting in a driver's seat and wearing a platinum blonde wig - with which she was associated.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was just coming off the huge success of her 2012 project 'Stranger Visions'.
In it, the artist produced portraits of strangers from forensic artefacts such as cigarette butts and chewing gum, extracting DNA from the waste to produce an image of what these people might look like.
That was when she received an email from a newspaper magazine.
"They were doing an interview with Chelsea Manning while she was in prison, and they wanted some kind of portrait to accompany that article," Dewey-Hagborg explained at a press preview of the new exhibition.
And she couldn't visit at the time and she couldn't be photographed, so you contacted Chelsea and asked her if she wanted to do a DNA portrait.
The artist and her imprisoned muse became unlikely pen pals, exchanging several letters over the course of two years.
They even created a comic strip, Suppressed Images, illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, which foresaw a future in which the president would commute Chelsea's sentence and she would be able to see the exhibition in person.
That Obama would actually call for Manning's release after seven brutal years in a Kansas military prison just days after the book was published was a welcome kind of serendipity.
There is something deep and strong about the show's opening now, too, as Donald Trump wages a war against government whistleblowers and transgender troops to find new, tweetable ways to further inflame the rigid divisions he was supposed to fix.
When Dewey-Hagborg was asked about the strange timing of all this, she said that "things happen for a reason".
In an artistic statement written on the gallery wall, Manning, with her oversized signature underneath (the "i" in her surname has a heart), called for an end to the "automatic fragmentation whose basis has been gender, race, sexuality and culture."
On the opposite wall is her mitochondrial DNA sequence - a centipede of Cs and Gs and As, written in pencil.
By including the 200 letters (or nucleotides according to the artist's sophisticated scientific lexicon), Dewey-Hagborg hoped to show how remarkably similar, at least in biological terms, we all are.
"What people will hopefully take away from this is that our genome doesn't care about who we are and how open genetic data is to interpretation and how subjective it is," said Dewey-Hagborg, whose 2007 video work, Spurious Memories, is also on view.
"DNA data can tell so many different stories, so this is 30 of those stories."
The final piece in the exhibition, kept in its own room, is a page from the comic novella mentioned above.
It shows Manning emerging from the disciplinary barracks of the United States like King-Kong, speakerphone in hand.
"If they cold-cock your speech, they've won," it says.
"So never shut up".
"It came straight from a letter she wrote me", said the artist, who greets from Philadelphia.
"I still get goosebumps when I talk about it."
Manning has yet to see the exhibition in person - as foreshadowed in the comic book - but if she does, she will be greeted by the masks in the middle of the room, her own genomic simulacra flocking like hordes of protesters.
This was also purposeful, like everything else in the exhibition, right down to the size (5 " 2, Manning's stature), with her genetic haplogroups written in pencil.
"In the past I've had them on the wall, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd," Dewey-Hagborg said of the portraits.
"I wanted it to feel like a mass movement that formed with Chelsea, like the movement that was behind her liberation as well."
University of Northwestern professor and Oxford University employee wanted for killing
A nationwide manhunt is underway for a professor at Northwestern University and an Oxford University employee who are wanted as suspects after a man was fatally stabbed in a luxury Chicago flat.
On Monday, arrest warrants were issued for Wyndham Lathem, 42, and Andrew Warren, 56, for murder for their alleged involvement in the death of Trenton H. James Cornell-Duranleau, Cook County District Court records show.
The documents say Cornell-Duranleau, 26, died after being stabbed multiple times.
A community alert released by the Chicago Police Department says the body was discovered on July 27.
Officers received a call, arrived at the Grand Plaza Apartments and found the victim with multiple injuries to his body.
Cornell-Duranleau was pronounced dead at the scene and detectives are investigating the stabbings as a homicide while police are actively searching for the two suspects, officials said.
Lathem has been an associate professor of microbiology and immunology at Northwestern University since 2007.
Alan K. Cubbage, the vice president for university relations, said in an emailed statement that Lathem would now be on leave and had been barred from entering the Northwestern University campus.
"This is now a criminal matter that is being investigated by the appropriate authorities, and Northwestern University is cooperating with that investigation," Cubbage said.
Warren is a senior treasury assistant at Oxford University.
A spokesperson for the university and Somerville College said in an emailed statement that "we are in contact with police in the UK and are prepared to assist US investigators in any way possible."
The statement added that Warren's colleagues were shocked and wanted him to turn himself in.
Chief Communications Officer for the Chicago Police Department Anthony Guglielmi said he urged the suspects to turn themselves in to authorities.
"Police have an idea of their whereabouts and our efforts to locate them are intensifying," Guglielmi said.
Guglielmi said local, regional and national authorities are helping to locate the suspects.
Guglielmi said police received a call from the building manager of the Grand Plaza building who had just received a mysterious tip that something had happened in flat 1008.
Police described the scene as very gruesome.
Guglielmi said it was unclear whether the incident also took place on 27 July.
It was confirmed by security cameras that Lathem and Warren were in the building.
"We believe Professor Latham and the victim had a relationship," Guglielmi said.
The Grand Plaza management team released a statement to residents: "Police are currently working on the timeline and background of the victim and are exploring a variety of motives, including a possible domestic incident."
"We will finalise the WADA roadmap in the near future" - Russian Deputy Prime Minister Mutko
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Vitaly Mutko said it would not take long to implement the remaining World Anti-Doping Agency (WADA) criteria for the restoration of the Russian Anti-Doping Agency (RUSADA).
"At a certain stage of meeting the criteria of the roadmap, RUSADA has been given the right to plan and test in cooperation with UKAD (UK Anti-Doping)," he said.
The WADA roadmap has been updated in this regard," Mutko said on Thursday.
The PM was commenting on the second part of WADA's code compliance roadmap, which outlines the criteria for RUSADA's reinstatement and was recently published on the organisation's website.
According to Mutko, it contains nothing that could cause concern for Russia.
"Everything has been announced, everything will be implemented.
And the results will be presented to the International Olympic Committee (IOC) and WADA in the near future," he added.
However, one of the criteria mentioned in the list states that Russian anti-doping authorities must publicly accept the reported results of the WADA-approved investigation by Canadian lawyer Richard McLaren into alleged state-sponsored doping in Russian sport.
Commenting on the matter, Mutko said, "We are conducting the investigation because our anti-doping system has admitted a mistake.
All measures have been implemented.
But there were no state programmes and we will not admit something that does not exist."
Mutko's words echoed those of Vitaly Smirnov, head of Russia's independent anti-doping commission.
Speaking to Russian outlet RSport earlier in the day, Smirnov admitted to past problems in Russian anti-doping organisations, but then added: "We have repeatedly said that the report contains controversial positions and regulations.
Nobody intends to accept this report unconditionally," Smirnov added.
RUSADA was barred by WADA from conducting doping tests in Russia in November 2015 in the wake of the doping scandal.
However, it was allowed to plan and coordinate tests under the supervision of international experts and UK Anti-Doping (UKAD).
After a visit to the organisation's headquarters in Moscow in July, WADA director general Olivier Niggli said RUSADA was "moving in the right direction" to be reinstated.
The start-ups that will help your company avoid becoming the next Uber
Amy Errett tried to gauge happiness at your e-commerce start-up among your employees, but the surveys didn't work.
Answers were often vague, unhelpful or - worse - fraudulent.
And even when you promised anonymity, some workers didn't trust the process.
"There was just never consistency and objectivity," said Errett, who runs the 75-person San Francisco e-commerce hair care company Madison Reed.
She called in outside people for help.
A new breed of human resources start-ups is growing to help companies figure out how their employees are feeling.
By creating and licensing software that has the specific purpose of measuring employee engagement, it allows companies to conduct surveys, target Special Groups and demographics, offer employees anonymity and complaint hotlines, and in some cases allow whistleblowers to bypass C-suite executives and go directly to the board of directors.
"They have tools now like Strava and Fitbit for tracking their health, but where's the Fitbit for your business?" said Jim Barnett, co-founder and chief executive of Redwood City start-up Glint, whose software analytics tools are used by companies to measure employee engagement.
Errett said she gained better insight into what your employees are thinking and feeling in her three years with Glint.
In addition to Snap surveys and surveys from specific teams, it provides a heat map of the company that shows at a glance which units have the most complaints and which leaders have low approval scores - so you can drill down into why.
Companies are coming to realise that staying on top of workplace culture is essential, lest you become the next Uber embroiled in scandal since a former employee published a blog post describing an environment of harassment where those who spoke were punished.
For start-ups like Glint, this desire for oversight is a lucrative business opportunity.
The global governance, regulation and compliance industry could be worth more than $118.7 billion in 2020, according to financial technology website Let's Talk Payments.
Denver, Colorado, start-up Convercent, which helps companies prevent and detect bad behaviour, saw a surge in interest and activity earlier this year amid the Uber case in disrepute.
Convercent has nearly 600 clients, including Airbnb, Microsoft and Tesla.
Uber recently signed up as a client.
Like Glint, Convercent lets companies send customised "pulse" surveys, collect confidential responses in real time and view heat maps of your problem areas.
It also offers an anonymous SMS hotline for employees to report bad behaviour.
And if the chief executive is involved, complaints go directly to the board.
"The court of public opinion has captured the regulators," said Patrick Quinlan, Convercent's founder and chief executive.
If a company is found to be treating its employees poorly or behaving unethically, it can face costly consequences through consumer boycotts, employee turnover and lawsuits, Quinlan said.
Ruby Tuesday, the restaurant chain with more than 25,000 employees and over 500 locations, has used Convercent for more than a year to ensure employees are aware of policies and procedures and have an easy way to reach their corporate headquarters.
Previously, if an employee wanted to report a problem, he or she had to find a phone number or email for corporate headquarters, file a formal complaint and hope that it was taken seriously.
It was often an intimidating and uncomfortable experience, said James Vitrano, Ruby Tuesdays general counsel, who said there was no good way to track employee complaints.
Now that the company uses Convercent, problems previously hidden by managers sitting in city or state offices - such as discrimination, harassment or unfair practices - can be identified and addressed more quickly.
"I can get closer to that holistic, 360-degree view into the employment experience," said Vitrano, who leads Ruby Tuesday's Risk Management Group.
"And we protect our shareholders from employment litigation."
Companies began taking ethics, values and employee engagement more seriously in 2002 after accounting firm Arthur Andersen collapsed over ethical violations caused by the Enron scandal, Quinlan said.
But it took "social media coming into its own" for companies to realise that you couldn't stop their dirty laundry from going online.
"Before using technology to monitor ethics, people used hope as a strategy," he said.
Both Glint and Convercent offer their software as a service, charging businesses recurring fees for the use of their products.
It's a business model and opportunity that has the approval of venture capital investors, who have backed both start-ups.
Convercent received $10 million in funding in February from the likes of Sapphire Ventures and Tola Capital, bringing its total capital raised to $47 million.
Glitter secured $10 million in November from Bessemer Venture Partners, bringing its total funding to $60 million.
These investments hardly come as a surprise, given the interconnected nature of business, culture and venture capital.
There is a growing body of research that shows today's workforce expects more from their jobs than ever before.
In competitive markets like Silicon Valley, high salaries and interesting projects are just stakes.
Employees want to feel that you are accepted and valued, and that you are giving your time to a company with a positive mission.
"When people are happy to be at a company, feel their voices are heard, and that the work you do is worthwhile, they feel more committed to making that company successful," said Nina McQueen, vice president of global benefits and employee experience at LinkedIn, which uses both Convercent and Glint.
Investors achieve returns when their portfolio companies are doing well. Companies do well when employees are engaged and engaged.
When third party analytics tools promise to increase employee engagement and engagement, it's no wonder you find support.
Employee engagement data matters according to workplace culture experts.
But the data is useless if a company's administrators don't take action.
In fact, when a company asks employees for their feedback, it may have an expectation that change is on the way.
And if change doesn't come quickly enough, or at all, it can breed disappointment and demotivate employees.
"If you ask for 4,000 suggestions, you have to be prepared to have 4,000 conversations," said Russell Raath, president of consulting at business management firm Kotter International, who has seen companies that have relied too heavily on collecting data.
"Because if you don't follow up employees will wonder, 'Did you really hear me?
Do you care?
And if you don't care, why should I? "
Madison Reed, who now conducts monthly staff surveys, was able to initiate same-day action when a problem is reported on Glint, Errett said.
And after gathering feedback from frustrated employees, she was able, through the speed of decision-making and quality of communication, to reorganise several teams within the company and add communications training to address the issues.
At Ruby Tuesday, the company is always gaining new insights about employees, and it hopes that in the long run, this will lead to better retention of workers in an industry known for high turnover.
"If you're not committed to creating a culture of transparency, you're going to lose people," Vitrano said.
"And if you lose people, you will lose customers.
And if you lose customers, you're going to lose businesses.
