Creating a graphic novel: A castle in the history of England
In its recent past, little Scotney Castle featured in a squeeze music video and was a loophole for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But Scotney has seen 700 years of turbulent history from its cosy perch in the Bewl River valley in Kent and has now become the inspiration for a graphic novel by Jamie Rhodes, a mop-haired Yorkshireman with a penchant for historical documents.
"I think it's so nice to look at the handwriting of someone who's been dead for 300 years," he says wistfully.
"What a personal connection to hold that letter in my hand."
'A Castle in England' spans the period from the Middle Ages to the Age of Edward, documenting the families who lived in Scotney. Each story has been illustrated by a different emerging British artist - Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg.
It is not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: He wrote 'Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories' in 2014, a collection inspired by documents in the British Library - a project he found unexpectedly emotional.
"I just had this reaction to the thumbprint on the side of a letter written by a double agent in the 1700s who worked for the Jacobins," he says.
"That's his thumbprint!
And letters always smell of smoke, because in those days you lit a fire for the light.
For someone living 300 years later, the smell has an effect as if they were there too.
Oh, I love archives!"
For someone so smitten with old papers that he's supported by the National Trust and Arts Council England and lived in a castle for nearly four months ("To be honest: I overstated my welcome a little") this all seems too good to be true.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the Victorian "new" castle, looking through the archives and studying the castle's many treasures and curiosities, such as the mounted hyena heads on the walls and the bottles that had spent centuries in the moat.
He wandered the grounds and ruins of the old castle, talking to landscape keepers, gardeners and sometimes the artists who were working on the illustrations for his book.
Then, at night, he "drank whiskey and started writing".
Scotney's intimate history is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained full access in 2006, when the last heiress, Elizabeth Hussey, died.
When Rhodes arrived a decade later, staff were just beginning to look after the archive, which he described as "hundreds of years of aristocrats saying 'Oh, throw it in the attic'".
Diaries, letters from the time of the English Empire, maps depicting who owned what: "You'd think land conflicts would be boring," Rhodes says, "but there was a birch tree two families fought over.
Boys, let it all go its way!"
Some of the stories in the collection use the castle as a starting point to delve into English history on a broader scale, including 'The Labourer', which follows a man who leaves the newly built castle to join the Peasants' Revolt of 1381.
"There is a record of a riot that occurred in the castle in 1380 in this book called 'Knightly Families of Kent and Sussex', " Rhodes says.
"The Peasants' Revolt started in that area and I thought a riot was a good place to start.
Maybe the two are connected?"
Other stories are firmly rooted in the castle's history - such as 'The Priest', which tells the story of the Jesuit priest the Darrell family hid for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or 'The Smuggler', which depicts 18th-century smuggler Arthur Darrell, who staged his own funeral by filling a coffin with stones (a discovery made years later when his coffin was unearthed).
The Darrells are Rhodes's favourite Scotney family: "The gentlemen seemed to be quite crooks, always running up debts and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
Other generations of Darrell men solved their debt crises by marrying rich old women - I imagine them as a bunch of good-looking lads, with a talent for wooing heiresses."
With his stint at the castle over, Rhodes is on the lookout for other unique writing experiences
He has completed a two-week stint in the Finnish wilderness for a graphic novel about Elämänmäki, the site of an early 20th century sanatorium that has since been reclaimed by nature.
But Scotney has a special place for him.
"I was sad to leave again," he says.
"It was like, 'Oh, now I have to deal with this damn life again.'"
