Or to put it in 2017 parlance: Maid
Trump's great achievement?
He makes Mitt Romney the epitome of common sense.
It has become a truism of the Trump era that the political divisions that have polarised the US electorate have also divided families in small ways.
Around Christmas and Thanksgiving, there were newspapers in the US with advice on how to deal with the horror of Trump-voting relatives.
We are all supposedly straining to burst our filter bubbles.
Less noticed has been Trump's power to bring families together.
I mention this because my cousin, a left-leaning poet who lives in Chicago and has long been involved with the Republicans in our family, visited me in New York this week.
She reminded me that unity against a common enemy can have a powerful effect.
With Trump in the White House, everyone she knows, including the Republican kin with whom she had fought for decades over policy, is suddenly and quite strangely on the same side.
Around the dinner table, this is certainly a good thing, but it strikes me in a broader context that it also carries significant risks.
The left has been strengthened by Trump, but the disfiguring effect of his presidency has the power to push us all to the right.
When we speak of "normalisation" and Trump, we are referring to the scary possibility that one day his antics will no longer repulse us.
However, there is an even scarier long-term scenario in which Trump "normalises" right-wing Republicans who suddenly appear to be the epitome of sanity compared to his standards.
I find myself these days afflicted with an active nostalgia for Mitt Romney's hilarious version of crazy - the dog on the roof of the car, the 14% income tax (but at least we knew what his tax return looked like) - both of which strike one as very mild offences indeed compared to Trump.
If Trump goes, the next Republican candidate will just have to be sane to qualify as an immeasurable improvement.
When my cousin was in town, we took our kids to the carousel in Central Park, the largest of the carousels in the New York Parks Department, and the best three bucks you can spend in town if you don't need caffeine.
The horses are enormous, the fibreglass designs on the central cylinder - all the clowns are snarling and the animals twist to look over their own shoulders in fear - extremely sinister, and the strumming music conveys this in a strange way.
So many clichés of a city disappoint: The views of tall buildings get old, the skylines become too familiar to offer much excitement, and the reality of the city doesn't live up to the dream.
Thirty-five years later, and I'm still not quite over the day I found out that Swiss Cottage is not, in fact, a Swiss cottage - the themed pub Ye Olde Swiss Cottage doesn't count - but a large roundabout in north London.
The Central Park roundabout is still a strangely magical experience, though, as two two-year-olds, an 11-year-old and two women in their 40s can go on it and all have a great time.
If I could have rated the carousel, I would have given it full marks, but luckily no one asked.
On the other hand, in a department store this week, I was forced to rate my "experience" with transactions on a scale of one to five stars before I could swipe my credit card.
At the coffee shop on the corner of my street, it's the same thing, plus the option to match the rating with a 15% tip - this for buying something over the counter.
