Red meat, dairy and chocolate could help alleviate IBD (inflammatory bowel disease)
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study claims just the opposite: a diet rich in meat-based proteins and dairy products could ease the symptoms of patients with inflammatory bowel disease.
The incurable condition, which affects around 1.3 million in the US and 300,000 in the UK, causes stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhoea, weight loss and extreme fatigue.
While sufferers are usually advised to avoid meat and dairy products to relieve their symptoms, researchers at Washington University found that the essential amino acid tryptophan from proteins helps develop immune cells that promote a tolerant gut.
Lead researcher, Dr Marco Colonna, explained that immune cells patrol the gut to ensure that harmful microbes hiding in food do not enter the body.
Cells capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that promote tolerance and protect the body without damaging sensitive tissues.
If the balance tilts too far towards inflammation, inflammatory bowel disease can result.
Experiments have found that a type of tolerance-promoting immune cell is present in mice that carry a certain bacterium in their guts.
And the bacterium requires tryptophan - one of the building blocks of proteins - to trigger the cells' appearance.
Professor Colonna said, "We have established a link between a species of bacteria - Lactobacillus reuteri - which is a normal part of the gut microbiome, and the development of a population of cells that promote tolerance.
The more tryptophan the mice had in their diet, the more they had of these immune cells."
He suggested that if the same system worked in humans, the combination of L. reuteri and a diet rich in tryptophan would promote more tolerant, less inflammatory gut environments.
Postdoctoral researcher Dr Luisa Cervantes-Barragan was investigating a type of immune cell that promotes tolerance when she found that one group of study mice had such cells, but another group of the same strain, but housed separately, did not.
She suspected that the difference had to do with the mice's gut microbiomes - the community of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
The guts of the mice were DNA sequenced and six species of bacteria were found to be present in the mice with the immune cells, but absent in the mice without them.
Mice were raised in a sterile environment so they lacked an intestinal microbiome and did not develop these types of immune cells, and they were given the L. reuteri and the immune cells emerged.
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in a liquid and then transferred small amounts of the liquid - without the bacteria - to immature immune cells isolated from the mice.
The immune cells developed into the tolerance-promoting cells.
When the active component was purified from the liquid, it turned out to be a by-product of tryptophan metabolism known as indole-3-lactic acid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of such cells increased by about 50 per cent, but when tryptophan levels were halved, the number of cells dropped by half.
Dr Cervantes-Barragan explained that humans have the same tolerance-promoting cells as mice, and that most of us protect L. reuteri in our gastrointestinal tracts.
It is not known whether tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri cause cells to develop in humans as they do in mice, but defects in genes related to tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
She said, "The development of these cells is probably something we want to promote because these cells control inflammation on the inner surface of the gut.
Potentially, high tryptophan levels in the presence of L. reuteri can lead to an expansion of this population."
