White House advertising costs taxpayers thousands
The White House's decision to fly a Navy helicopter to South Lawn for an event highlighting American manufacturing last month cost taxpayers as much as $24,000, according to military figures provided to TIME magazine.
The green-and-white Sikorsky VH-3D, known as Marine One when the president is on board, was the centrepiece of the July 17 event at the White House featuring American builders.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured products from all 50 states.
The Connecticut-built helicopter was displayed alongside a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin and a forklift from Mississippi.
The White House military office requested the helicopter's presence in a fragmentary order, or FRAGO, barely 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the South Lawn, according to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit responsible for operating the helicopter.
"I just wanted you to be aware of this because it is such an unusual high visibility event," the commander of HMX-1 wrote to his superior, the deputy naval commander for aviation, on the eve of the event.
The note indicated that the helicopter arrived on the South Lawn at about 7am on 17 July for the 3pm event, and stayed until the lawn was cleared between 6pm and 9pm that evening.
The note adds that if the departure from the White House was delayed, a second crew would be needed for the return flight due to the restriction on duty hours.
The original flight crew was with the helicopter during the event, while the unit's security personnel remained with the aircraft while it was on the ground.
It was not clear from the records provided to TIME whether a second flight crew was ultimately required.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
Records indicate HMX-1 asked whether the event could violate the provision.
"One question we asked was whether it was a violation of the Hatch Act and we were informed that it was not," the commander wrote.
"Sounds like you are being cagey," the deputy commander replied.
The "Made in America" event was designated by the White House as an official event and would not have been covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official events have political overtones.
At the event, the president gave a push for health care reform that was underway in the Senate, and he touted efforts to rein in government regulations.
The use of the aircraft known as Marine One or Air Force One for politically advantageous purposes is hardly a new phenomenon.
Presidents are required to use them for travel.
But requesting its use just for a photo-op is unusual.
Trump conducted an investigation in February when the presidential plane provided taxi services against the backdrop of his first campaign rally in Melbourne, Florida, and his Twitter account is full of messages complaining about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is excited about the Made In America show - which features products from all 50 states made by American workers with American materials," said White House Deputy Press Secretary Lindsay Walters.
HMX-1 crews frequently conduct training flights around Washington and the South Lawn to drop the US president at the White House with precise centimetres.
When Trump was in Germany for the G20 summit in early July, HMX-1 conducted 58 practice landings at the White House.
The flight for the "Made in America" event counted in the aircrew's training requirement for the month, an official said.
Helicopter units flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidential support missions".
The White House said taxpayers did not shoulder the burden for any of the other props unveiled at the event.
A Sikorsky spokesman said the company was not involved in displaying the helicopter on the South Lawn.
HMX-1 does not maintain budget records for the presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact cost of the event.
However, according to US Department of Defence hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the DoD reimbursement rate for the VH-3D is $24,380 per flight hour.
Unit records list the aircraft's flight time as 30 minutes from the Marine Corps Air Facility home base at Quantico in Virginia.
The White House argues that the actual cost of operating the helicopter is far less than this rate.
"Basing the cost to taxpayers on reimbursement rate estimates is highly misleading," Walters said.
"These estimates include personnel, maintenance and many other hidden costs that are included in the annual appropriation."
According to a 2015 RAND study, DoD reimbursement rates do not include personnel costs, but take into account fuel, maintenance and contracting costs.
