Afghan democracy depends on women's political role, says UN
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, play a role, the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan said on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, acting head of the United Nations mission, said hundreds of women will run in provincial council elections. Three women are running for the role of vice president and more than 30 percent of newly registered voters are women.
"The role of women cannot be overestimated," he said in a statement on Wednesday.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women participate fully and are included in all parts of the electoral process, he added.
Afghan provincial council and presidential elections will be held on 5 April.
The Taliban have issued threats against an electoral process that coincides with the transition from international combat operations to an advisory role.
This year's elections will be the first time power has passed peacefully from one democratically elected government to the next.
Haysom said a strong role for women will add to Afghanistan's democratic success.
The Afghan Independent Election Commission reported that 1.2 million women were registered to vote out of a total of 3.6 million registered voters.
GMB concerns over investment at McVitie factory in Glasgow
A union is seeking assurances from managers at biscuit manufacturer McVitie about its long-term commitment to production at its Glasgow factory.
GMB Scotland said the company had been silent about the future of investment at the Tollcross site.
More than 500 people work at the plant, which makes Hobnobs and Rich Tea biscuits among other products.
McVities owner Pladis said he had invested more than £5 million in recent years.
He added that staff and union representatives would be "the first to know" if their operations changed.
In a letter to the company's branch manager, GMB Scotland urged McVitie's to "raise concerns that funding for upgrading production lines is not being progressed".
GMB senior organiser Drew Duffy, said, "The failure to gain clarity from the general site manager on the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross deeply concerns our members.
Generations of families have worked here and the workforce is heavily focused on the local community and Greater Glasgow, a key pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Therefore, from a jobs, pay and prosperity perspective, and against a backdrop of Brexit, rising living costs and chronic manufacturing decline, the east end of Glasgow desperately needs a thriving manufacturing presence at McVitie."
A spokeswoman for Pladis said, "The store manager at Tollcross received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday and the company will be responding directly as we value the ongoing engagement with staff and union representatives.
We had a regular meeting with staff and GMB representatives at Tollcross two months ago where some issues were openly discussed.
We discussed with staff that, like all companies operating in a highly competitive and uncertain economic climate, we are constantly reviewing our businesses - and this applies to all our divisions and sites - in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years we have invested more than £5 million in our Tollcross site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We fully recognise Tollcross' heritage as a manufacturing site. If there are any changes to our site operations, employees and their union representatives will be the first to know."
Did PSG warn Barcelona about Neymar three years ago?
La Liga side may rue their interest in Marco Verratti
Paris Saint-Germain will not relent in their pursuit of Neymar after making a £189m bid to trigger his release clause, but did they warn Barcelona about the world-record hold-up three years ago?
The sensational approach has fuelled the summer transfer window as the Ligue 1 club look set to break the world record by more than double the previous mark, with Paul Pogba returning to Manchester United for £89m last season.
Once completed, Neymar will become the world's most expensive player and the highest-paid professional athlete in the world. PSG are offering wages of more than £500,000 a week.
Barcelona are furious at the way Neymar has forced his way out, although a source close to the Catalan board insists the club have always done their best to look after him since his arrival from Santos in 2013.
But was the football world warned about this prospect by the PSG president three years ago?
When Manchester City expressed interest in signing Blaise Matuidi in 2014, Nasser Al-Khelaifi had a stern warning for any club looking to sign one of PSG's best players.
"I am not worried because they know that if they touch one of our players then we will be in opposition to them, we will contact their players," Al-Khelaifi said.
"We respect all clubs.
But if they try to sign one of our players with them, there will be consequences."
Barcelona appear to have crossed that line, with the Spanish club expressing interest in PSG midfielder Marco Verratti earlier this summer.
PSG made it clear they would not allow the Italy international to leave under any circumstances, and Barcelona could feel the consequences of that interest by losing one of their price bids for Neymar.
